# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: california-gold-rush
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:california-gold-rush/1920s-florida-land-boom] The first real estate bubble in Florida was primarily driven by the 1920s economic prosperity, coupled with a lack of understanding of storm frequency and poor building standards.
[src:california-gold-rush/1920s-florida-land-boom] This pioneering era of Florida land speculation lasted from 1924 to 1926 and attracted investors from all over the nation.
[src:california-gold-rush/1920s-florida-land-boom] The land boom left behind entirely new, planned developments incorporated into towns and cities.
[src:california-gold-rush/1920s-florida-land-boom] Major investors and speculators such as Carl G.
[src:california-gold-rush/1920s-florida-land-boom] Fisher also left behind a new history of racially deed restricted properties that segregated cities for decades.
[src:california-gold-rush/1920s-florida-land-boom] Among those cities at the center of this bubble were Miami Beach, Coral Gables, Hialeah, Miami Springs, Opa-locka, Miami Shores, and Hollywood.
[src:california-gold-rush/1920s-florida-land-boom] It also left behind the remains of failed development projects such as Aladdin City, Boca Raton (original plan), Chevelier, Fulford-by-the-Sea, Interocean City, Isola di Lolando, Okeelanta, Palm Beach Ocean, Poinciana, and Sun City.
[src:california-gold-rush/1920s-florida-land-boom] The land boom shaped Florida's future for decades and created entire new cities out of the Everglades land that remain today.
[src:california-gold-rush/1920s-florida-land-boom] In the background were the well-publicized extensions of the Florida East Coast Railway, first to West Palm Beach (1894), then Miami (1896), and finally Key West, 1912.
[src:california-gold-rush/1920s-florida-land-boom] The Everglades were being drained, creating new dry land.
[src:california-gold-rush/1920s-florida-land-boom] Finally, World War I cut off the rich from their seasons on the French Riviera, increasing the appeal of parts of the U.S. with a Mediterranean or Tropical climate.
[src:california-gold-rush/1920s-florida-land-boom] The economic prosperity of the 1920s, coupled with a lack of knowledge about storm frequency and the poor building standards used by boom developers, set the conditions for the first real estate bubble in Florida.
[src:california-gold-rush/1920s-florida-land-boom] Miami had an image as a tropical paradise, and outside investors across the United States began taking an interest in Miami real estate.
[src:california-gold-rush/1920s-florida-land-boom] In part due to publicity stunts and deed restrictions, developers saw a large influx of Northern tourists and potential residents.
[src:california-gold-rush/1920s-florida-land-boom] Fisher of Indiana became famous by purchasing a huge lighted billboard in New York's Times Square proclaiming "It's June In Miami".
[src:california-gold-rush/1920s-florida-land-boom] Fisher's publicity and investments, along with those of concurrent pioneers Lummus and Collins, correlated with rapidly rising prices, and the boom began.
[src:california-gold-rush/1920s-florida-land-boom] Brokers and dealers also speculated wildly on commodities.
[src:california-gold-rush/1920s-florida-land-boom] They ordered supplies in excess of what was actually needed and sent shipments to general destinations.
[src:california-gold-rush/1920s-florida-land-boom] As a result, railroad freight cars became stranded, choking rail traffic statewide.
[src:california-gold-rush/1920s-florida-land-boom] The impact of the boom would extend beyond Miami and southern Florida.
[src:california-gold-rush/1920s-florida-land-boom] Tampa saw growth during this period as well, but had a more diversified economy than Miami, which included manufacturing and tourism.
[src:california-gold-rush/1920s-florida-land-boom] Miami's economy was primarily based on tourism, despite failed attempts during the 1920s to diversify the city's economy.
[src:california-gold-rush/1920s-florida-land-boom] Jacksonville, the largest city in Florida, would not be as affected by the boom because municipal leaders had decided to work on expanding industry and commerce rather than tourism after World War I.
[src:california-gold-rush/1920s-florida-land-boom] By January 1925, investors were beginning to read negative press about Florida investments.
[src:california-gold-rush/1920s-florida-land-boom] *Forbes* magazine warned that Florida land prices were based solely upon the expectation of finding a customer, not upon any real land value.
[src:california-gold-rush/1920s-florida-land-boom] The Bureau of Internal Revenue began to scrutinize the Florida real estate boom as a giant sham operation.
[src:california-gold-rush/1920s-florida-land-boom] Speculators intent on flipping properties for huge profits began to have difficulty finding new buyers.
[src:california-gold-rush/1920s-florida-land-boom] Also in 1925, Florida began to pass laws further regulating real estate; with salesmen being required to have licenses and offices which as a result led to a boom in demand for office space.
[src:california-gold-rush/1920s-florida-land-boom] On January 10, 1926, the *Prinz Valdemar*, a 241-foot, steel-hulled schooner, sank in the mouth of the turning basin of Miami harbor and blocked access to the harbor.
[src:california-gold-rush/1920s-florida-land-boom] It had been on its way to becoming a floating hotel.
[src:california-gold-rush/1920s-florida-land-boom] Because the railroads were still embargoing non-essential shipments, it became completely impossible to bring building supplies into the Miami area, and the city's image as a tropical paradise began to crumble.
[src:california-gold-rush/1920s-florida-land-boom] In his book *Miami Millions*, Kenneth Ballinger wrote that the *Prinz Valdemar* capsize incident saved many people from huge possible losses by revealing cracks in the Miami façade.
[src:california-gold-rush/1920s-florida-land-boom] The days of Miami properties being bought and sold at auction as many as ten times in one day were over.
[src:california-gold-rush/1920s-florida-land-boom] Although the railroads lifted the embargo in May 1926, the boom was about to end.
[src:california-gold-rush/1920s-florida-land-boom] The 1926 Miami hurricane ended the boom and the much smaller 1928 Okeechobee hurricane made certain it was extinguished.
[src:california-gold-rush/1920s-florida-land-boom] The 1926 hurricane destroyed "whatever public enthusiasm for Florida vacation properties and real estate development that remained," as there had been little preparation for the storm.
[src:california-gold-rush/1920s-florida-land-boom] Florida's economic decline predated the start of the Great Depression.
[src:california-gold-rush/1920s-florida-land-boom] Therefore, it had fewer resources and more debt than other regions of the nation.
[src:california-gold-rush/1920s-florida-land-boom] Large amounts of local debt financing through bonds worsened the state's economic situation, most of it stemming from the years of the land boom.
[src:california-gold-rush/1920s-florida-land-boom] During the land boom, many local governments sold bonds to finance development-related projects.
[src:california-gold-rush/1920s-florida-land-boom] After the boom, the local government did not have revenue proceeds to pay down bond debt.
[src:california-gold-rush/1920s-florida-land-boom] This resulted in widespread unsecured bond default.
[src:california-gold-rush/1920s-florida-land-boom] Another contributing factor was that numerous counties in southern Florida took out large loans during the boom to help fund infrastructure projects to entice developers, leading these counties into debt.
[src:california-gold-rush/1920s-florida-land-boom] Doyle Carlton was elected in 1928 as governor and during his tenure he tried to put a limit on the amount of bonded debt local governments could hold.
[src:california-gold-rush/1920s-florida-land-boom] He faced opposition from state representatives in northern Florida whose counties had less debt and did not want to pay for their southern counterparts.
[src:california-gold-rush/1920s-florida-land-boom] Deposits in Florida banks had increased steadily between 1922 and 1925, but then started to decline; by 1926 smaller banks began to fail because of many withdrawals by depositors and defaults on loans.
[src:california-gold-rush/1920s-florida-land-boom] Bank assets flowing into the state started to reverse.
[src:california-gold-rush/1920s-florida-land-boom] A "surplus of funds" and easily available credit also began to dry up.
[src:california-gold-rush/1920s-florida-land-boom] The collapse of land values in Florida caused a severe financial crisis for the state government.
[src:california-gold-rush/1920s-florida-land-boom] Land values had dropped nearly to the vanishing point, but the property was subject to property tax assessments far in excess of its current value.
[src:california-gold-rush/1920s-florida-land-boom] Many property owners simply abandoned the property and did not pay the taxes.
[src:california-gold-rush/1920s-florida-land-boom] Under state law, the state could not sell the property for less than its assessed value.
[src:california-gold-rush/1920s-florida-land-boom] To remedy the situation, in 1937, the Florida Legislature passed the Murphy Act.
[src:california-gold-rush/1920s-florida-land-boom] The Act permitted the state to sell tax delinquent property for what could be obtained.
[src:california-gold-rush/1920s-florida-land-boom] Deeds issued to purchasers, colloquially known as “Murphy deeds,” reserved certain rights to the state.
[src:california-gold-rush/1920s-florida-land-boom] Years later, these reservations, in many cases, enabled the state to acquire rights-of-way without paying compensation.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-commodities-boom] The **1970s commodities boom** refers to the rise of many commodity prices in the 1970s.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-commodities-boom] Excess demand was created with money supply increasing too much and supply shocks that came from Arab–Israeli conflict, initially between Israel and Egypt.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-commodities-boom] The Six-Day War where Israel captured and occupied the Sinai Peninsula for 15 years, the Closure of the Suez Canal (1967–1975) for 8 years of that, led to supply shocks.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-commodities-boom] 66% of oil consumed by Europe at that time came through the Suez Canal and had to be redirected around the continent of Africa.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-commodities-boom] 15% of all maritime trade passed through the Suez Canal in 1966, the year before it closed.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-commodities-boom] The Yom Kippur War in late 1973 was Egypts attempt at crossing the Suez Canal and taking the Sinai Peninsula back from Israeli occupation.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-commodities-boom] On October 19, 1973 Richard Nixon requested $2.2 billion to support Israel in the Yom Kippur War.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-commodities-boom] That resulted in OAPEC countries cutting production of oil and placing an embargo on oil exports to the United States and other countries backing Israel.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-commodities-boom] That was the start of the 1973 oil crisis.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-commodities-boom] In the early 1970s, the Soviet Union and many other planned economies started importing large amounts of grains in the global markets, driving up demand for grains and oilseeds.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-commodities-boom] Sugar prices spiked in the 1970s because of Soviet Union demand/hoarding and possible futures contracts market manipulation.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-commodities-boom] The Soviet Union was the largest producer of sugar at the time.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-commodities-boom] In 1974, Coca-Cola switched over to high-fructose corn syrup because of the elevated prices.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-commodities-boom] The price of coffee went up in the mid-1970s because of a black frost of 1975 that killed 66% of Brazil's coffee trees, which was the number one producer of coffee at the time.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-commodities-boom] There was a big earthquake in 1976 in Guatemala that disrupted supply chains, the world's fifth biggest coffee exporter at the time.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-commodities-boom] The Angolan Civil War started in 1975 disrupting their coffee production and shipping.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-commodities-boom] The United States weaned itself off the gold standard in the 1970s, allowing the price of gold to float.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-commodities-boom] The price of gold went from a set exchange rate of $42.22 per troy ounce in 1973 to almost $200 per ounce in 1976.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-commodities-boom] Price controls were implemented in the early 1970s to combat inflation but when those price controls were lifted on commodities like copper the prices appreciated.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-commodities-boom] These quick price rises were known as the Nixon shock.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-commodities-boom] Coal price increases in the 1970s were primarily demand driven.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-commodities-boom] There was a strike by the United Mine Workers of America called The Brookside Strike in late 1974 that lasted for 3 weeks but was said to have little impact on prices.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-commodities-boom] After World War II the Bretton Woods system had fixed exchange rates between countries and pegged to gold.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-commodities-boom] This kept some commodities like gold very stable.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-commodities-boom] When the Bretton Woods system failed in the early 1970s and floating exchange rates started to float, commodities also became very volatile.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] The **1970s energy crisis** occurred when the Western world, particularly the United States, Canada, Western Europe, Australia, and New Zealand, experienced substantial petroleum shortages as well as elevated prices.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] The two worst crises of this period were the 1973 oil crisis and the 1979 oil crisis, when, respectively, the Yom Kippur War and the Iranian Revolution triggered interruptions in Middle Eastern oil exports.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] The crisis began to unfold as petroleum production in the United States and some other parts of the world peaked in the late 1960s and early 1970s.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] World oil production per capita began a long-term decline after 1979.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] The oil crises prompted the first shift towards energy-saving (in particular, fossil fuel-saving) technologies.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] The major industrial centers of the world were forced to contend with escalating issues related to petroleum supply.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] Western countries relied on the resources of countries in the Middle East and other parts of the world.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] The crisis led to stagnant economic growth in many countries as oil prices surged.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] Although there were genuine concerns with supply, part of the run-up in prices resulted from the perception of a crisis.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] The combination of stagnant growth and price inflation during this era led to the coinage of the term *stagflation*.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] By the 1980s, both the recessions of the 1970s and adjustments in local economies to become more efficient in petroleum usage, controlled demand sufficiently for petroleum prices worldwide to return to more sustainable levels.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] The period was not uniformly negative for all economies.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] Petroleum-rich countries in the Middle East benefited from increased prices and the slowing production in other areas of the world.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] Some other countries, such as Norway, Mexico, and Venezuela, benefited as well.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] In the United States, Texas and Alaska, as well as some other oil-producing areas, experienced major economic booms due to soaring oil prices even as most of the rest of the nation struggled with the stagnant economy.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] Many of these economic gains, however, came to a halt as prices stabilized and dropped in the 1980s.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] Conflict between Arabs and Israelis in the Middle East has existed since Israel's declaration of independence in 1948, including a number of wars.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] The 1956 Suez Crisis, also known as the Second Arab–Israeli war, was sparked when Israel's southern port of Eilat was blocked by Egypt, which also nationalized the Suez Canal belonging to Anglo-French investors.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] One of the objectives of the Anglo-French-Israeli invasion was the removal of President Gamal Abdel Nasser who was aligning with the Soviet Union.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] The Six-Day War of 1967 included an Israeli invasion of the Egyptian Sinai Peninsula, which resulted in Egypt's closure of the Suez Canal for eight years after Israel occupied the Sinai Peninsula.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] The canal was cleared in 1974 and opened again in 1975 after the 1973 Yom Kippur War, when Egypt tried and failed to take back the Sinai Peninsula.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] OAPEC countries cut production of oil and placed an embargo on oil exports to the United States after Richard Nixon requested $2.2 billion to support Israel in the war after learning that the Soviet Union, was aiding Syria and Egypt in the war.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] Nevertheless, the embargo lasted only until January 1974, though the price of oil remained high afterwards.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] The real price of petroleum was stable in the 1970 timeframe, but there had been a sharp increase in American imports, putting a strain on American balance of trade, alongside other developed nations.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] During the 1960s, petroleum production in some of the world's top producers with extraction technology at the time began to peak.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] West Germany reached its production peak in 1966, Venezuela and the United States in 1970, and Iran in 1974.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] Canada's conventional oil production peaked around the same time (though non-conventional production later helped revive Canadian production to some degree).
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] The worldwide production per capita peaked soon afterward.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] Although production in other parts of the world was increasing, the peaks in these regions began to put substantial upward pressure on world oil prices.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] Equally as important, control of the oil supply became an increasingly important problem as countries like West Germany and the U.S. became increasingly dependent on foreign suppliers for this key resource.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] The 1973 oil crisis was a direct consequence of the U.S production peak in late 1960 and the beginning of 1971 (and shortages, especially for heating oil, started from there).
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] The "embargo" as described below is the "practical name" given to the crisis.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] For the main Arab producers, the "embargo" supposedly allowed them to show to "the Arab street" that they were doing something to support Egypt in reclaiming its territory in Sinai and Gaza.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] In reality, it was more a desire to punish the U.S for re-supplying Israel with weapons during the Yom Kippur War, after the Soviet Union re-supplied Syria and Egypt with weapons.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] In real market terms (number of barrels) the embargo was almost a non-event, as it was only conducted by a few countries, against a few countries.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] The embargo was never effective from Saudi Arabia towards the US, as reported by James E.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] Akins in interview at 24:10 in the documentary "la face cachée du pétrole part 2".
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] Akins, who audited US capacity for Nixon after US peak, was US ambassador in Saudi Arabia at that time.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] Lawrence Rocks and Richard Runyon captured the unfolding of these events at the time in The Energy Crisis book.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] OAPEC declared it would limit or stop oil shipments to the United States and other countries if they supported Israel in the conflict.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] With the US actions seen as initiating the oil embargo, the long-term possibility of embargo-related high oil prices, disrupted supply and recession, created a strong rift within NATO; both European countries and Japan sought to disassociate themselves from the US Middle East policy.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] Arab oil producers had also linked the end of the embargo with successful US efforts to create peace in the Middle East, which complicated the situation.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] To address these developments, the Nixon Administration began parallel negotiations with both Arab oil producers to end the embargo, and with Egypt, Syria, and Israel to arrange an Israeli pull back from the Sinai and the Golan Heights after the fighting stopped.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] By January 18, 1974, Secretary of State Henry Kissinger had negotiated an Israeli troop withdrawal from parts of the Sinai.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] The promise of a negotiated settlement between Israel and Syria was sufficient to convince Arab oil producers to lift the embargo in March 1974.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] By May, Israel agreed to withdraw from parts of the Golan Heights close to the Syrian border.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] Independently, the OPEC members agreed to use their leverage over the world price-setting mechanism for oil to stabilize their real incomes by raising world oil prices.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] This action followed several years of steep income declines after the recent failure of negotiations with the major Western oil companies earlier in the month.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] For the most part, industrialized economies relied on crude oil, and OPEC was a major supplier.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] Because of the dramatic inflation experienced during this period, a popular economic theory has been that these price increases were to blame, as being suppressive of economic activity.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] However, the causality stated by this theory is often questioned.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] The targeted countries responded with a wide variety of new, and mostly permanent, initiatives to contain their further dependency.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] The 1973 "oil price shock", along with the 1973–1974 stock market crash, have been regarded as the first event since the Great Depression to have a persistent economic effect.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] A crisis emerged in the United States in 1979 during the wake of the Iranian Revolution.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] Amid massive protests, the Shah of Iran, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, fled his country in early 1979, allowing the Ayatollah Khomeini to gain control.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] The protests shattered the Iranian oil sector.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] While the new regime resumed oil exports, it was inconsistent and at a lower volume, forcing prices to go up.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] Saudi Arabia and other OPEC nations, under the presidency of Dr.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] Mana Alotaiba increased production to offset the decline, and the overall loss in production was about 4 percent.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] However, a widespread panic resulted, driving the price far higher than would be expected under normal circumstances.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] In 1980, following the Iraqi invasion of Iran, oil production in Iran nearly stopped, and Iraq's oil production was severely cut as well.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] Afterwards, oil prices began a decline as other countries began to fill the production shortfalls from Iran and Iraq.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] The 1973 and 1979 energy crisis had caused petroleum prices to peak in 1980 at over US$35 per barrel (US$137 in today's dollars).
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] Following these events slowing industrial economies and stabilization of supply and demand caused prices to begin falling in the 1980s.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] The glut began in the early 1980s as a result of slowed economic activity in industrial countries (due to the 1973 and 1979 energy crises) and the energy conservation spurred by high fuel prices.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] The inflation adjusted real 2004 dollar value of oil fell from an average of $78.2 per barrel in 1981 to an average of $26.8 in 1986.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] This sentiment was echoed in November 1981, when the CEO of Exxon also characterized the glut as a temporary surplus, and that the word "glut" was an example of "our American penchant for exaggerated language".
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] He wrote that the main cause of the glut was declining consumption.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] In the United States, Europe and Japan, oil consumption had fallen 13% from 1979 to 1981, due to "in part, in reaction to the very large increases in oil prices by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries and other oil exporters", continuing a trend begun during the 1973 price increases.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] After 1980, reduced demand and overproduction produced a glut on the world market, causing a six-year-long decline in oil prices culminating with a 46 percent price drop in 1986.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] The U.S. reported negative economic growth during the 1970s and remained weak till the 1980s as the post World War II economic boom drew to a close.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] Other causes that contributed to the recession included the Vietnam War, which turned out costly for the United States and the fall of the Bretton Woods system.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] The emergence of newly industrialized countries rose competition in the metal industry, triggering a steel crisis, where industrial core areas in North America and Europe were forced to re-structure.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] The 1973–1974 stock market crash made the recession evident.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] According to the National Bureau of Economic Research, the U.S. economy slid into a recession in 1973–75.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] Inflation levels remained high even when an economic expansion took place afterwards.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] During this recession, the Gross Domestic Product of the United States fell 3.2%.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] Although the recession ended in March 1975, the unemployment rate did not peak for several months.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] In May 1975, the rate reached its height for the cycle of 9%.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] The recession also lasted from 1973 to 1975 in the United Kingdom.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] The GDP declined by 3.9% or 3.37% depending on the source.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] It took 14 quarters for the UK's GDP to recover to that at the start of recession.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] High oil prices in the 1970s induced investment in oil production by non-OPEC countries, particularly for reserves with a higher cost of production.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] These included Prudhoe Bay in Alaska, the North Sea offshore fields of the United Kingdom and Norway, the Cantarell offshore field of Mexico, and oil sands in Canada.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] As a result of the 1973 crisis many nations created strategic petroleum reserves (SPRs), crude oil inventories (or stockpiles) held by the governments of particular countries or private industry, for the purpose of providing economic and national security during an energy crisis.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] The International Energy Agency (IEA) was formed in the wake of this crisis and currently comprises 31 member countries.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] According to the IEA, approximately 4.1 billion barrels (650,000,000 m3) of oil are held in strategic reserves by the member countries, of which 1.4 billion barrels (220,000,000 m3) is government-controlled.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] The remainder is held by private industry.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] These reserves are intended to be equivalent to at least 90 days of net imports.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] Strategic Petroleum Reserve is one of the largest government-owned reserves, with a capacity of up to 713.5 million barrels (113,440,000 m3).
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] Recently, other non-IEA countries have begun creating their own strategic petroleum reserves, with China being the second largest overall and the largest non-IEA country.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] Since Israel's declaration of independence in 1948 this state has found itself in nearly continual conflict with the Arab world and some other predominantly Muslim countries.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] The animosity between the Arabs and the Israelis became a global issue during the 1970s.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] The Yom Kippur War of 1973, with the supplying of Israel by its Western allies while some Arab states received Soviet supplies, made this one of the most internationally threatening confrontations of the period.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] The large oil discoveries in the Middle East gave some Muslim countries unique leverage in the world, beginning in the 1960s.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] The 1973 and 1979 crises, in particular, were demonstrations of the new power that these countries had found.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] The United States and other countries were forced to become more involved in the conflicts between these states and Israel.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] One of the first challenges OPEC faced in the 1970s was the United States' unilaterally pulling out of the Bretton Woods Accord and taking the U.S. off the established Gold Exchange Standard in 1971.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] The change resulted in instability in world currencies and depreciation of the value of the U.S. dollar, as well as other currencies.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] The revenues of OPEC also took a hit since they priced oil in dollars.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] Finally OPEC started pricing oil against gold to combat the situation.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] But OPEC still struggled to maintain stability in the region as the negotiations between them and other Western oil companies bore little to no positive results.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] The major oil-producing regions of the U.S.—Texas, Oklahoma, Louisiana, Colorado, Wyoming, and Alaska—benefited greatly from the price inflation of the 1970s as did the U.S. oil industry in general.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] Oil prices generally increased throughout the decade; between 1978 and 1980 the price of West Texas Intermediate crude oil increased 250 percent.
[src:california-gold-rush/1970s-energy-crisis] Although all states felt the effects of the stock market crash and related national economic problems, the economic benefits of increased oil revenue in the Oil Patch states generally offset much of this.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1974-stock-market-crash] The **1973–1974 stock market crash** caused a bear market between January 1973 and December 1974.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1974-stock-market-crash] Affecting all the major stock markets in the world, particularly the United Kingdom, it was one of the worst stock market downturns since the Great Depression, the other being the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1974-stock-market-crash] The crash came after the collapse of the Bretton Woods system over the previous two years, with the associated 'Nixon Shock' and United States dollar devaluation under the Smithsonian Agreement.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1974-stock-market-crash] It was compounded by the outbreak of the 1973 oil crisis.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1974-stock-market-crash] It was a major event of the 1970s recession.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1974-stock-market-crash] All the main stock indices of the future G7 bottomed out between September and December 1974, having lost at least 34% of their value in nominal terms and 43% in real terms.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1974-stock-market-crash] West Germany's market was the fastest to recover, returning to the same level by June 1985.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1974-stock-market-crash] The United Kingdom returned to the same market level by May 1987, but this full recovery lasted for only a few months and ended with the Black Monday crash of 1987.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1974-stock-market-crash] The United States returned to the same market level by August 1993, over twenty years after the 1973–74 crash began.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1974-stock-market-crash] In the 694 days between 11 January 1973 and 6 December 1974, the New York Stock Exchange's Dow Jones Industrial Average benchmark suffered the seventh-worst bear market in its history, losing over 45% of its value.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1974-stock-market-crash] The year 1972 had been a good year for the DJIA, with gains of 15% in the twelve months, and 1973 had been expected to be even better, with Time magazine reporting just 3 days before the crash began that it was 'shaping up as a gilt-edged year'.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1974-stock-market-crash] In the two years from 1972 to 1974, the American economy slowed from 7.2% real GDP growth to −2.1% contraction, while inflation (by CPI) jumped from 3.4% in 1972 to 12.3% in 1974.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1974-stock-market-crash] The Dow reached its lowest level, 577.60 points, on December 6, 1974.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1974-stock-market-crash] The effect was worse in the United Kingdom, particularly on the London Stock Exchange's FT 30, which lost 73% of its value during the crash.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1974-stock-market-crash] From a rate of 5.1% real GDP growth in 1972, the UK went into recession in 1974, with GDP falling by 1.1%.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1974-stock-market-crash] At the time, the UK's property market was going through a major crisis, and a secondary banking crisis forced the Bank of England to bail out a number of lenders.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1974-stock-market-crash] In the United Kingdom, the crash ended after the rent freeze was lifted on 19 December 1974, allowing a readjustment of property prices; over the following year, stock prices rose by 150%.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1974-stock-market-crash] The definitive market low for the FT30 Index (a forerunner of the FTSE100 today) came on 6 January 1975, when the index closed at 146 (having reached a nadir of 145.8 intra-day).
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1974-stock-market-crash] The market then practically doubled in just over 3 months.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1974-stock-market-crash] However, unlike in the United States, inflation continued to rise, to 25% in 1975, giving way to the era of stagflation.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1974-stock-market-crash] The Hong Kong Hang Seng Index also fell from 1,800 in early 1973 to close to 300.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1974-stock-market-crash] Out of the 20 largest percentage gains and losses in the DJIA, none occurred during this time period.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1974-stock-market-crash] In all cases, the recovery was a slow process.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1974-stock-market-crash] Although West Germany's market was the fastest to recover, returning to the original nominal level within eighteen months, it did not return to the same real level until June 1985.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1974-stock-market-crash] The United Kingdom did not return to the same market level until May 1987 (only a few months before the Black Monday crash), whilst the United States did not see the same level in real terms until August 1993, over twenty years after the 1973–74 crash began.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1974-stock-market-crash] The Hong Kong TVB series *The Greed of Man* storyline revolves around the market crash.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1975-recession] The **1973–1975 recession** or **1970s recession** was a period of economic stagnation in much of the Western world (i.e. the United States, Canada, Western Europe, Australia, and New Zealand) during the 1970s, putting an end to the overall post–World War II economic expansion.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1975-recession] It differed from many previous recessions by involving stagflation, in which high unemployment and high inflation existed simultaneously.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1975-recession] Among the causes were the 1973 oil crisis, the deficits of the Vietnam War, and the fall of the Bretton Woods system after the Nixon shock.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1975-recession] The emergence of newly industrialized countries increased competition in the metal industry, triggering a steel crisis, where industrial core areas in North America and Europe were forced to re-structure.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1975-recession] The 1973–74 stock market crash made the recession evident.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1975-recession] Although the economy was expanding from 1975 to the first recession of the early 1980s, which began in January 1980, inflation remained extremely high until the early 1980s.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1975-recession] Bureau of Labor Statistics estimates that 2.3 million jobs were lost during the recession; at the time, this was a post-war record.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1975-recession] In May 1975, the rate reached its height for the cycle of 9 percent.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1975-recession] GDP declined by 3.9% depending on the source.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1975-recession] The oil crisis was largely to blame for the downturn in the United Kingdom, just as it was in the US, although an additional crisis came in the form of the Three-Day Week, which was the result of fears over power shortages as a miner's strike was announced in December 1973.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1975-recession] Electricity blackouts across the country were widespread.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1975-recession] There was also double-digit inflation during this period, which peaked at more than 20%.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1975-recession] Edward Heath's offer of a 13% pay rise was rejected by the miners.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1975-recession] He responded by calling a snap election on 28 February 1974 in what he saw as an opportunity for the electorate to show the miners that the government – and not the miners or the unions – were responsible for running the country.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1975-recession] Most opinion polls suggested that the Tories would be re-elected with a majority, but when the election results came through on the morning of 1 March 1974, no party had an overall majority.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1975-recession] The gap between Ted Heath's Tory government and the Labour opposition led by Harold Wilson, who had been prime minister for nearly six years until his surprise defeat by Heath's Tories in the 1970 election, was so narrow that the Tories received the most votes, but Labour won slightly more seats.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1975-recession] Economic growth was re-established in 1975 as the recession's end was declared, but Britain's economy remained shaky.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1975-recession] The Labour government's tiny majority was wiped out by early 1977 as a result of by-election defeats, and Callaghan managed to form a coalition with the Liberals to hang onto power.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1975-recession] The pact concluded in the summer of 1978, by which time economic growth had picked up (although unemployment now stood at a postwar high of 1,500,000), and opinion polls suggested that Labour could form a majority government if a general election was held.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1975-recession] Callaghan ruled out an election in September 1978, and within weeks a series of strikes began which would spark the Winter of Discontent.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1975-recession] In March 1979, a vote of no confidence issued by Tory opposition leader Margaret Thatcher sparked the collapse of the Labour government and in the election in May that year, the Tories returned to power.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1975-recession] In the first year of the Thatcher-led Tory government inflation rose to 15.3%, but then fell to 5% by the time of their election win in 1983.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1975-recession] However, the monetarist policies designed to curb inflation caused a recession in 1980 and resulted in a steep rise in unemployment from 5.4% (1,390,46 people) to 11.5% (3,104,66 people).
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1975-recession] It was not until 2000, by which time Labour had been re-elected as New Labour under Tony Blair that unemployment fell to the level in 1979.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1975-recession] West Germany, Europe's largest economy at the time, had the largest post-war GDP fall in 1975.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1975-recession] During the recession industrial production fell and inflation was 5%.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1975-recession] In Sweden, the recession proved devastating to the shipping, ship-building, and logging and mining industries.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1975-recession] The increase in oil prices caused export revenues from shipping to drop by 25% within a few years.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1975-recession] Sweden at this time had the world's second largest ship building industry after Japan, and the spillover effects devastated shipbuilders.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1975-recession] Swedish shipbuilders lost some 3 billion SEK in 1974, which led to problems in Sweden's steel industry.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1975-recession] The loss of shipbuilding jobs devastated port cities such as Malmö, home to Kockums' shipyard, which struggled for the next 20 years.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1975-recession] The ripple effects compounded issues in the iron ore mining industry, at a time when Swedish iron ore was experiencing rising mining costs and facing increased low-cost competition from new mines in places such as Australia and Brazil.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1975-recession] The inflationary recession, combined with an expansionary government fiscal policy and a generous collective wage agreement among unions in 1974–1976, put Sweden on a highly inflationary path: the price index quintupled between 1972 and 1995.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1975-recession] The oil crisis of 1973 also had similarly large negative effects on other countries that relied heavily on imported oil, such as France, Sweden, Japan, Finland, Belgium, Luxembourg, and Denmark.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1975-recession] These countries gained increased market share both in their domestic markets and abroad at accelerating rates during the 1970s.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1975-recession] In the United States, the economic recovery from the 1973 to 1975 recession had many of the characteristics of a typical U-type recovery.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1975-recession] GNP (the measure at the time) reached and exceeded its pre-recession level by first quarter 1976.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1975-recession] Industrial production had recovered to its pre-recession levels by the end of 1976.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1975-recession] The major influence of the experience of the 1974 recession came in the form of the concept of stagflation, that is, inflation during a period of recession.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1975-recession] The Federal Reserve adjusted its mandate as a result, believing that the inflation-unemployment tradeoff was much higher than previously thought, and established a 6% target as full employment.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1975-recession] Thus, unemployment, which had reached a peak of 9% in May 1975, did not dip below 6% until June 1978.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1975-recession] The pre-1974 recession level of 4.6% unemployment was not reached again until November 1997, when the Federal Reserve deviated from its prior policy.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1975-recession] The interpretation regarding the cause of stagflation was and continues to be controversial.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1975-recession] The oil embargo of 1973–1974, which pushed prices of petroleum from $15 to $45 a barrel (2010 dollars) almost overnight, certainly contributed to inflationary measures during this period, taking a larger share of incomes (an "oil tax") at a time of falling consumer spending.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-1975-recession] The price of petroleum products continued to rise throughout the decade, reaching a peak of about $73 a barrel (2010 dollars) in 1979 as a result of the Iranian revolution, a price not exceeded until 2008 in the wake of dislocations due to the war in Iraq.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In an effort that was led by Faisal of Saudi Arabia, the initial countries that OAPEC targeted were Canada, Japan, the Netherlands, the United Kingdom, and the United States.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] This list was later expanded to include Portugal, Rhodesia, and South Africa.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In March 1974, OAPEC lifted the embargo, but the price of oil had risen by nearly 300%: from US$3 per barrel ($19/m3) to nearly US$12 per barrel ($75/m3) globally.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Prices in the United States were significantly higher than the global average.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] After it was implemented, the embargo caused an oil crisis, or "shock", with many short- and long-term effects on the global economy as well as on global politics.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The 1973 embargo later came to be referred to as the **first oil shock**.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] A second oil shock occurred in 1979 in the aftermath of the Iranian Revolution.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Following the Israeli Declaration of Independence in 1948, there has been conflict between Arabs and Israelis in the Middle East, including several wars.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Suez Crisis, also known as the Second Arab–Israeli war, was sparked by Israel's southern port of Eilat being blocked by Egypt, which also nationalized the Suez Canal belonging to French and British investors.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] As a result of the war, the Suez Canal was closed for several months between 1956 and 1957.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Six-Day War of 1967 included an Israeli invasion of the Egyptian Sinai Peninsula, which resulted in Egypt closing the Suez Canal for eight years.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Following the Yom Kippur War, the canal was cleared in 1974 and opened again in 1975.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OAPEC countries cut production of oil and placed an embargo on oil exports to the United States after Richard Nixon requested $2.2 billion to support Israel's war effort.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] By 1969, American domestic production of oil was peaking and could not keep pace with increasing demand from vehicles.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The US was importing 350 million barrels (56 million cubic metres) per year by the late 1950s, mostly from Venezuela and Canada.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Because of transportation costs and tariffs, it never purchased much oil from the Middle East.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1973, US production had declined to 16% of global output.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Eisenhower imposed quotas on foreign oil that would stay in place between 1959 and 1973.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Critics called it the "drain America first" policy.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Some scholars believe the policy contributed to the decline of domestic US oil production in the early 1970s.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The cheapness of oil compared with coal led to the decline of the coal industry.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1951, 51% of the United States' energy came from coal, and by 1973, only 19% of American industry was coal-based.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The decline in domestic oil production, combined with the country's increasing reliance on oil as a source of power, made the US economy vulnerable to a foreign oil embargo.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] When Richard Nixon became US president in 1969, he assigned George Shultz to head a committee to review the Eisenhower-era quota program.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Shultz's committee recommended that the quotas be abolished and replaced with tariffs, but Nixon decided to keep the quotas due to vigorous political opposition.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon imposed a price ceiling on oil in August 1971 as demand for oil was increasing and production was declining, which increased dependence on oil imports as consumption was bolstered by low prices.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1973, Nixon announced the end of the quota system.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Between 1970 and 1973 US imports of crude oil had nearly doubled, reaching 6.2 million barrels per day in 1973.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Until 1973, an abundance of oil supply had kept the market price of oil lower than the posted price.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1970, American oil production peaked and the United States began to import more oil.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Oil imports rose by 52% between 1969 and 1972.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] By 1972, 83% of the American oil imports came from the Middle East.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Throughout the 1960s, the price for a barrel of oil remained at $1.80, meaning that with the effects of inflation considered the price of oil in real terms got progressively lower throughout the decade, with Americans paying less for oil in 1969 than they had in 1959.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Even after a price for a barrel of oil rose to $2.00 in 1971, adjusted for inflation, people in the Western nations were paying less for oil in 1971 than they had in 1958.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The extremely low price of oil served as the basis for the "long summer" of prosperity and mass affluence that began in 1945.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC), was founded by five oil producing countries at a Baghdad conference on 14 September 1960.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The five founding members of OPEC were Venezuela, Iraq, Saudi Arabia, Iran and Kuwait.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OPEC was organized after the oil companies slashed the posted price of oil, but the posted price of oil remained consistently higher than the market price of oil between 1961 and 1972.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1963, the Seven Sisters controlled 86% of the oil produced by OPEC countries, but by 1970 the rise of "independent oil companies" had decreased their share to 77%.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The entry of three new oil producers—Algeria, Libya and Nigeria—meant that by 1970, 81 oil companies were doing business in the Middle East.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In the early 1960s Libya, Indonesia and Qatar joined OPEC.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OPEC was generally regarded as ineffective until political turbulence in Libya and Iraq strengthened their position in 1970.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Additionally, increasing Soviet influence provided oil producing countries with alternative means of transporting oil to markets.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Under the Tehran Price Agreement of 1971, signed on 14 February, the posted price of oil was increased and, due to a decline in the value of the US dollar relative to gold, certain anti-inflationary measures were enacted.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] A severe drain on US gold reserves lead to higher inflation and lack of confidence in the strength of the dollar, President Nixon issued Executive Order 11615 on August 15, 1971, which closed the gold window.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] This action made the dollar inconvertible to gold directly, except on the open market, and was soon dubbed the *Nixon Shock*, leading eventually to the collapse of the Bretton Woods system in 1976.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Because oil was priced in dollars, oil producers' real income decreased when the dollar started to float free of the old link to gold.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In September 1971, OPEC issued a joint communiqué stating that from then on, they would price oil in terms of a fixed amount of gold.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] After 1971, OPEC was slow to readjust prices to reflect this depreciation.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] From 1947 to 1967, the dollar price of oil had risen by less than two percent per year.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Until the oil shock, the price had also remained fairly stable versus other currencies and commodities.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OPEC ministers had not developed institutional mechanisms to update prices in sync with changing market conditions, so their real incomes lagged.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The substantial price increases of 1973–1974 largely returned their prices and corresponding incomes to former levels in terms of commodities such as gold.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Arab oil producing countries had attempted to use oil as leverage to influence political events on two prior occasions—the first was the Suez Crisis in 1956 when the United Kingdom, France and Israel invaded Egypt.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] During the conflict the Syrians sabotaged both the Trans-Arabian Pipeline and the Iraq–Baniyas pipeline, which disrupted the supply of oil to Western Europe.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The second instance was when war broke out between Egypt and Israel in 1967, but despite continued Egyptian and Syrian enmity against Israel, the embargo lasted only a few months.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Most scholars agree that the 1967 embargo was ineffective.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Although some members of the Organization of Arab Petroleum Exporting Countries (OAPEC) supported the use of oil as a weapon to influence the political outcome of the Arab–Israeli conflict, Saudi Arabia had traditionally been the strongest supporter of separating oil from politics.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Saudis were wary of the tactic due to the availability of oil from non-Arab oil producing countries, and in the decades leading up to the crisis, the region's conservative monarchies had grown dependent on Western support to ensure their continued survival as Nasserism gained traction.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On the other hand, Algeria, Iraq and Libya had strongly supported the use of oil as a weapon in the conflict.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Arab newspapers like the Egyptian *Al-Ahram*, Lebanese *An-Nahar* and Iraqi *Al-Thawra* had historically been supportive of the use of oil as a weapon.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1970, President Nasser of Egypt died and was succeeded by Anwar Sadat, a man who believed in the diplomacy of surprise, in engaging in sudden moves to upset the diplomatic equilibrium.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Sadat liked to say that his favourite game was backgammon, a game where skill and persistence was rewarded, but was best won by sudden gambles, making an analogy between how he played backgammon and conducted his diplomacy.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Under Nasser, Egypt and Saudi Arabia had engaged what was known as the Arab Cold War, but Sadat got along very well with King Faisal of Saudi Arabia, forming an alliance between the most populous Arab state and the wealthiest Arab state.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Unlike the secularist Nasser, Sadat was a pious Muslim and he had a strong personal rapport with King Faisal, who was an equally pious Muslim.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The man largely in charge of American foreign policy, the National Security Adviser, Henry Kissinger, later admitted that he was so engrossed with the Paris peace talks to end the Vietnam war that he and others in Washington missed the significance of the Egyptian-Saudi alliance.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At the same time that Sadat moved closer to Saudi Arabia, he also wanted a rapprochement with the United States and to move Egypt away from its alliance with the Soviet Union.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1971, the US had information that the Arab states were willing to implement another embargo.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In July 1972, Sadat expelled all 16,000 of the Soviet military personnel in Egypt in a signal that he wanted better relations with the United States.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger was taken completely by surprise by Sadat's move, saying: "Why has he done me this favor?
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] For Sadat, cost was no object as the money to buy Soviet arms came from Saudi Arabia.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At the same time, Faisal promised Sadat that if it should come to war, Saudi Arabia would embargo oil to the West.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In April 1973, the Saudi Oil Minister Ahmed Zaki Yamani visited Washington to meet Kissinger and told him that King Faisal was becoming more and more unhappy with the United States, saying he wanted America to pressure Israel to return all the lands captured in the Six Day War of 1967.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In a later interview, Yamani accused Kissinger of not taking his warning seriously, saying all he did was to ask him not to speak anymore of this threat.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Angry at Kissinger, Yamani, in an interview with the *Washington Post* on April 19, 1973, warned that King Faisal was considering an oil embargo.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At the time, the general feeling in Washington was the Saudis were bluffing and nothing would come of their threat to impose an oil embargo.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The fact that Faisal's ineffectual half brother King Saud had imposed a crippling oil embargo on Britain and France during the Suez War of 1956 was not considered an important precedent.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The CEOs of four of the United States' oil companies, after speaking with Faisal, arrived in Washington in May 1973 with the warning that Faisal was considerably tougher, more intelligent and more ruthless than his half-brother Saud whom he had deposed in 1964, and that his threats were serious.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger declined to meet the four CEOs.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In an assessment done by Kissinger and his staff about the Middle East in the summer of 1973, the repeated statements by Sadat about waging *jihad* against Israel were dismissed as empty talk, while the warnings from King Faisal were likewise regarded as inconsequential.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In September 1973, Nixon fired Rogers as Secretary of State and replaced him with Kissinger.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger later stated he had not been given enough time to know the Middle East, as he settled into the State Department's office at Foggy Bottom as Egypt and Syria attacked Israel on 6 October 1973.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 6 October 1973, the Yom Kippur began when Egypt attacked the Bar Lev Line in the Sinai Peninsula and Syria launched an offensive in the Golan Heights, both of which had been occupied by Israel during the 1967 Six-Day War.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal of Saudi Arabia was supportive, and on 8 October 1973, he told two Egyptian envoys: "You have made us all proud.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In the past we could not lift our heads up.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] He promised to give to Egypt a quality of aid worth $200 million US dollars to assist with the war effort, and stated he was willing to use the "oil weapon" if necessary to support Egypt.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The war began during the height of the Watergate scandal; as such Nixon largely let Kissinger manage foreign policy as he, Nixon, was distracted by the scandal.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger promised Israeli Prime Minister Golda Meir that the United States would replace its losses in equipment after the war.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon had ordered an arms lift to Israel on 12 October 1973, but Kissinger used the excuse of bureaucratic delays to limit the amount of weapons and ammunition sent to Israel.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Arab concept of the "peace of the brave", i.e. a victorious leader being magnanimous to his defeated opponents, meant there was a possibility that Sadat at least would make peace with Israel provided that the war ended in such a way that Egypt was not perceived to be defeated.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Likewise, Kissinger regarded Meir as being rather arrogant and believed that an armistice that ended the war in a manner that was not an unambiguous Israeli victory would make her more humble.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] As both Syria and Egypt lost much equipment during the fighting, the Soviet Union began to fly new equipment in, starting on 12 October.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Soviet flights to Syria and Egypt were recorded by the British radar stations in Cyprus.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Though the Soviets were flying in an average of 60 flights per day, exaggerated accounts appeared in Western newspapers speaking of "one hundred flights per day".
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At this point, both Nixon and Kissinger began to see the October War more in terms of the Cold War rather than Middle Eastern politics, both seeing the Soviet arms lifts to Egypt and Syria as a Soviet power play that required an American answer.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On October 12, 1973, US president Richard Nixon authorized Operation Nickel Grass, a strategic airlift to deliver weapons and supplies to Israel in order to replace its materiel losses.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The first American weapons to Israel arrived on 15 October 1973, and despite Nixon's orders the number of American planes flying into Tel Aviv were initially limited.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] After the first week of the war, the Israelis had halted the Syrian offensive in the Golan Heights and were pushing back the Syrians back towards Damascus.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Along the Suez canal, however, there was heavy fighting, with the Egyptians holding their own.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At an OPEC summit at the Sheraton Hotel in Kuwait City on 16 October 1973, it was announced the price of oil would go from $3.01 US dollars per barrel to $5.12 per barrel.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The news about the war on 16 October was grim from the Arab viewpoint, with the Syrians steadily being pushed back, while Israelis had opened a counter-offensive against the Egyptians and crossed the Great Bitter Lake.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Responses from stated representatives at the meeting were varied.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Saudi Oil Minister Ahmed Zaki Yamani stated, in a 1981 interview, that "[t]he king still wanted to give America a chance to stay out of the fighting.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] So we agreed to cut back production by just 5 percent per month.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] A full embargo, we agreed, was something we would implement only if we felt that things were absolutely hopeless".
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Iranian delegation left the summit after agreeing to the price increase, as the Shah of Iran only supported higher oil prices.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Oil Minister of Iraq, Sa'dun Hammadi demanded the "total nationalization" of all assets of American oil companies in the Middle East, the withdrawal of all Arab funds from the United States and for all Arab states to break diplomatic relations with the United States.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Libyan Oil Minister, Izz al-Din al-Mabruk, called for the nationalization of all the assets of all Western oil companies in the Middle East.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Saudi delegation led by Yemani, supported by the Algerian delegation, fought hard against the Iraqi and Libyan demands for an embargo, as Yemani maintained that forcing through an increase in the price of oil was the best way to influence the United States.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Hammadi and the rest of the Iraqi delegation left upset as Yemani had won over the majority of the delegations to the Saudi viewpoint.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The statement issued after midnight at the Sheraton Hotel was handwritten and, reflecting the tense talk, had several paragraphs crossed out while other paragraphs were written in by different hands.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 17 October, Arab oil producers cut production by 5% and threatened an oil embargo against Israel's wartime allies: the United States, the Netherlands, Rhodesia, South Africa, and Portugal.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 17–19 October 1973, the Saudi Foreign Minister, Omar Al Saqqaf, visited Washington together with the foreign ministers of Algeria, Kuwait and Morocco to warn that there was a real possibility of an oil embargo being imposed.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon promised him that the United States would mediate a settlement to the war that would be "peaceful, just and honorable" to both sides.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] He had ended the Vietnam war on what he felt was an honorable basis and now intended to end the October war in the same manner.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Saqqaf complained to King Faisal that Nixon seemed more interested in a dispute about "a burglary" (i.e. the Watergate scandal) than about the war.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] During a press conference, an American reporter mocked the threat of an embargo, contemptuously saying the Saudis "could drink their oil", leading Saqqaf to reply in anger "All right, we will!".
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Israel took heavy losses in men and materiel during the fighting against Egypt and Syria, and on 18 October 1973, Meir requested $850 million worth of American arms and equipment to replace its materiel losses.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon decided, characteristically, to act on an epic scale; Instead of the $850 million worth of arms requested, he sent a request to Congress for some $2.2 billion worth of arms to Israel, which was promptly approved.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon, whose administration was being badly battered by the Watergate scandal, felt that a bold foreign policy move might resuscitate his administration.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In an interview with the British historian Robert Lacey in 1981, Kissinger later admitted about the arms lift to Israel: "I made a mistake.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In retrospect it was not the best considered decision we made".
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The arms lift enraged King Faisal of Saudi Arabia.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal was angry that Israel had only asked for $850 million worth of American weapons, and instead received an unsolicited $2.2 billion worth of weapons, which he perceived as a sign of the pro-Israeli slant of American foreign policy.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal also felt insulted that Nixon had just promised Saqqaf an "honorable" peace the day before he submitted the request to Congress for some $2.2 billion worth of arms for Israel, which he saw as an act of duplicity on Nixon's part.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal had been opposed to a total embargo and only agreed to the 5% cut on 17 October under pressure from other Arab states.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal felt his efforts on behalf the United States were not being appreciated in Washington, which increased his fury at Nixon.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On the afternoon of 19 October 1973, Faisal was in his office when he learned about the United States sending $2.2 billion worth of weapons to Israel, and discussed the issue with two of his closest advisers, Abdullah ibn Abdul Rahman and Rashad Pharaon.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The king called Yamani at about 8 pm, and told him he was needed at the Riyassa Palace immediately.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Yamani told the king: "The TV news goes out at nine.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] If you make a decision now, we can get it announced at once".
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The king replied "Write this down" and announced he was placing a total embargo on the United States.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Most of the other oil-producing Arab states joined the embargo.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Algeria, Iraq, and Libya promoted the embargo, but did not actively enforce it.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The embargo was accompanied by gradual monthly production cuts—by December, production had been cut to 25% of September levels.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] This contributed to a global recession and increased tension between the United States and several of its European allies, who faulted the US for provoking an embargo by providing what many viewed as unconditional assistance to Israel.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OAPEC demanded a complete Israeli withdrawal from all territories beyond the 1949 Armistice border.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The embargo lasted from October 1973 to March 1974.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Because every Arab state except for Iraq and Libya joined the oil embargo, oil exports from the Middle East to the West were down by 60–70% by November 1973.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Japan and the nations of western Europe imported some 75% of their oil from the Near East.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The embargo led to immediate and sharp price raises, as Lacey noted that "competing desperately for dwindling supplies, consumers showed themselves willing to pay unparalleled money for their oil".
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Saudi Arabia had 25% of the world's oil reserves.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The embargo imposed on the United States led to shortages of oil in the United States, which set an inflationary spiral, as the new high prices for oil in the American market led to sharp increases of the price of oil in nations not subjected to the embargo.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] When the Iranian state oil company held an auction on 16 December 1973, bids for some $17 US dollars per barrel of oil were made.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In late December 1973, OPEC held a conference in Vienna when it was announced the price for a barrel of oil was to increase from $5 US dollars per barrel to $11.65 US dollars per barrel.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal was opposed to the price increase, which was largely the work of the Iranian delegation.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 22 February 1974, King Faisal chaired the second summit of Islamic states in Lahore, which, unlike the first summit that Faisal had chaired in 1969, was not boycotted by Iraq and Syria.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal was acclaimed as a conquering hero who humiliated and humbled the West by wrecking its economy.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The prime minister of Pakistan, Zulfikar Ali Bhutto, opened the conference by stating: "The armies of Pakistan are the armies of Islam.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On November 7, 1973, Kissinger flew to Riyadh to meet King Faisal and ask him to end the oil embargo in exchange for promising to be "evenhanded" with the Arab-Israeli dispute.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] As the plane carrying him prepared to land in Riyadh, Kissinger was clearly nervous at the prospect of negotiating with the stern Wahhabi Faisal who had a marked dislike of Jews.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] During a summit in Cairo the day before, Kissinger asked Sadat what Faisal was like and was told: "Well, Dr.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Henry, he will probably go on with you about Communism and the Jews".
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] King Faisal's two great hatreds were communism and Zionism, as he believed that the Soviet Union and Israel were plotting together against Islam.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Initially, Secretary of Defense James Schlesinger suggested to Kissinger that the USA invade Saudi Arabia and another Arab countries and seize their oil fields.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger stated in a private state department meeting that it's “ridiculous that the civilized world is held up by 8 million savages...
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Can’t we overthrow one of the sheikhs just to show that we can do it?” They formed a plan to invade Abu Dhabi, Kuwait, and Saudi Arabia.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger publicly threatened "countermeasures" in a November 21, 1973 press conference if the embargo was not lifted, and the Saudis responded with threatening further oil cuts and to burn their oil fields if the US military invaded.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] After the CIA confirmed these threats, Kissinger gave up military intervention and decided to deal with Israel's troop withdrawals, settling on diplomatic solutions to the oil embargo.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 18 March 1974, King Faisal ended the oil embargo.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Sadat had reported to Faisal that the United States was being more "evenhanded", and Kissinger had promised to sell Saudi Arabia weapons that it had previously denied under the grounds that they might be used against Israel.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Since Israeli forces did not withdraw to the 1949 Armistice Line, the majority of scholars believe that the embargo was a failure.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Roy Licklieder, in his 1988 book *Political Power and the Arab Oil Weapon*, concluded that the embargo was a failure because the countries that were targeted by the embargo did not change their policies on the Arab–Israeli conflict.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Licklieder believed that any long term changes were caused by the OPEC increase in the posted price of oil, and not the OAPEC embargo.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Daniel Yergin, on the other hand, has said that the embargo "remade the international economy".
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Over the long term, the oil embargo changed the nature of policy in the West towards increased exploration, alternative energy research, energy conservation and more restrictive monetary policy to better fight inflation.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p01] For further details see the "Energy crisis" series by Facts on File.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The effects of the embargo were immediate.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] OPEC forced oil companies to increase payments drastically.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The price of oil quadrupled by 1974 from US$3 to nearly US$12 per 42 gallon barrel ($75 per cubic meter), equivalent in 2018 dollars to a price rise from $17 to $61 per barrel.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Saudi Arabia had 25% of the world's oil, but only 4% of the oil used in the United States in 1973 came from the kingdom.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] However, Saudi Arabia plays an over-sized role within the Arab world.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In 1973, about 25% of the oil used in the United States came from Arab countries.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The shortage of oil within the United States caused by the Arab oil embargo forced prices to rise, which led price rises globally.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Oil producers that had not joined the embargo such as Iran, Venezuela, Libya and Iraq demanded higher prices in Japan and Europe, as an initiative to ship oil to those places instead of the United States, setting off a worldwide inflationary spiral.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Although the embargo did not severely disrupt US oil supplies—since Americans imported more oil from non-embargoed nations such as Iran—the resulting 400% increase in oil prices caused by the embargo damaged the American economy.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] A number of nations such as Venezuela, Nigeria, Iran and Iraq increased their oil production during the embargo, and sold their oil at a higher price.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The leader who pushed the most for higher oil prices was the Shah of Iran, and the Italian historian Giuliano Garavini has argued that the leader most responsible for the West's economic problems during the "oil shock" was not King Faisal, but rather the Shah.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Some of the nations that were classified as "friendly" to the Arab viewpoint in regards to the Arab-Israeli dispute such as France and Belgium were the ones who suffered the most from the worldwide inflation caused by the embargo.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In March 1974, the crisis eased when the embargo was lifted after negotiations at the Washington Oil Summit, but the effects lingered throughout the 1970s.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The dollar price of energy increased again in 1975, amid the weakening competitive position of the dollar in world markets.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Arab oil embargo ended the long period of prosperity in the West that had begun in 1945, throwing the world's economy into the steepest economic contraction since the Great Depression.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The "long summer" of prosperity in the post-war years had made possible the "swinging sixties" and the related rise of a rebellious youth culture, as it was easy to be hedonist or in rebellion against traditional values in a time of unprecedented prosperity.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] 1945 to 1973 had been a period of unprecedented prosperity in the West, a "long summer" that many believed would never end.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Its abrupt end in 1973, as the oil embargo increased the price of oil by 400% within a matter of days and threw the world's economy into a sharp recession, with unemployment mounting and inflation raging, came as a profound shock.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The end of what the French called the *Trente Glorieuses* ("Glorious Thirty" [years]) led to widespread pessimism in the West, with the *Financial Times* running a famous headline in late 1973 saying, "The Future will be subject to Delay".
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In an August 1974 address to the General Assembly, Kurt Waldheim, the secretary-general of the United Nations, complained about "the note of helplessness and fatalism creeping into world affairs".
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The sudden and abrupt end of the "long summer" of prosperity in 1973-1974 played a major role in the pessimistic mood that characterized the culture of the West of the 1970s.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In 1975, a report to Congress from the Federal Energy Administration estimated that the embargo of 1973–1974 had caused about 500,000 Americans to lose their jobs, and caused a GNP loss between $10 billion–$20 billion.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] This price increase had a dramatic effect on oil exporting nations, for the countries of the Middle East who had long been dominated by the industrial powers were seen to have taken control of a vital commodity.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil-exporting nations began to accumulate vast wealth.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Some of the income was dispensed in the form of aid to other underdeveloped nations whose economies had been caught between higher oil prices and lower prices for their own export commodities, amid shrinking Western demand.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Much went for arms purchases that exacerbated political tensions, particularly in the Middle East.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The 400% increase in the world oil prices led to extravagant promises being made by the leaders of oil-producing nations.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Shah of Iran told his subjects in a speech in December 1973 that he was launching "Great Civilization" project that would make Iran into a First World nation by the 1990s.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] President Carlos Andrés Pérez of Venezuela likewise launched his *Le Gran Venezuela* project intended to make Venezuela into a First World nation.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] President Yakubu Gowon of Nigeria told his people that henceforward Nigeria's main problem would be "managing abundance".
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] After the oil shock, Nigeria presented itself as the first African nation that would reach First World status.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In Lagos, a series of stately modernist buildings were erected as appropriate for a nation that saw itself as the leader of all Black Africa.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Much of the oil wealth in Nigeria was stolen by corrupt politicians.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] At least some of Nigeria's new oil wealth went to rebuild the areas devastated by the civil war of 1967-1970 and to address the complaints that too much of Nigeria's oil wealth went to the federal government in Lagos instead of the people.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The new wealth generated by the "oil shock" allowed for Chairman Houari Boumédiène of Algeria to become a global leader, courted by elites in the First World and the Third World.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil embargo led a sudden interest in the Palestinian issue.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Between 1973 and 1981, Saudi Arabia donated a sum worth $1 billion US dollars to the Palestine Liberation Organization, which thus had a budget that exceeded that of many Third World nations.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On November 8, 1973, Kissinger became the first Secretary of State to meet with a Saudi leader since 1953, as he met King Faisal to ask him to end the embargo.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Within two week of the embargo being launched, all of the foreign ministers of the nations of the European Economic Community, now the European Union, met in a conference to issue a statement calling for Israel "to end the territorial occupation which has maintained since the conflict of 1967".
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On December 11, 1973, the Japanese Foreign Minister Masayoshi Ōhira flew in to Riyadh to meet King Faisal for "talks on improving bilateral relations".
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Shortly afterwards, the French foreign minister Michel Jobert arrived to sign an agreement that provided oil for France for the next twenty years.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On January 24, 1974, as the Shah of Iran, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, was coming off the ski slopes of St.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Moritz, he was met by the British Chancellor of Exchequer, Anthony Barber, and the Trade Secretary, Peter Walker.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In a role-reversal, Barber and Walker paid homage to the Shah, who promised them that his nation would sell the United Kingdom 5 million tons of oil in exchange for some £100 million of British goods, to aid his plans to industrialize Iran.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Saudi Arabia experienced an upsurge of prosperity and affluence after the oil embargo, whose consequences horrified King Faisal.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Faisal, who was devoted to a harsh puritanical strain of Sunni Islam known in the West as Wahhabism, was appalled by the way that his subjects became materialistic, devoted only to conspicuous consumption and greed as they lost interest in Islam.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Lacey wrote: "The spiritual dangers of easy affluence distressed him more.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] His simple gesture of piety and honor seemed to have opened a Pandora's Box that threatened to turn his realm into a parody of all he held dear".
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In the last two of years of his life, Faisal fell into depression over the way his subjects had been seduced into a consumerist lifestyle, becoming lost in a sense of "melancholia".
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Faisal's son, Crown Prince Mohammad told Lacey in 1981: "The profligacy, the greed, he felt he could not stem it.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] He become so bound up in his work, there was almost nothing private of him left".
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] A sign of the changed values was that despite the total ban on alcohol in Saudi Arabia, drinking and drug use became common with the younger members of the House of Saud.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] James Akins, the American ambassador in Riyadh reported; "the sky over Riyadh is black with vultures with new get-richer-quicker plans under their wings".
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In 1974, property prices in Riyadh doubled on a weekly basis for the entire year, as the prosperity led to a real estate speculation bubble that was often compared to the Klondike gold rush of 1898–1899.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] At the Red Sea port of Jeddah, there were so many ships queuing up laden with cement for the construction boom in Saudi Arabia, that construction contractors hired helicopters to fly the cement in, twenty bags per flight.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] A number of families engaged in the Saudi construction industry such as the Juffali, Alireza, al-Khasshoggi and the bin Laden families all became very wealthy as a result of the construction boom.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The period after the oil shock of 1973–1974 is still fondly remembered in Saudi Arabia as the "age of abundance", where nearly everyone had a significant increase in their standard of living.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The wealth and corruption generated by the oil shock led to a fundamentalist backlash in Saudi Arabia.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On 20 November 1979, Islam's holiest shrine, the Grand Mosque of Mecca, was seized by a group who proclaimed themselves to be the followers of the Mahdi, a messianic figure said to appear at the dawn of every Muslim century to strike down the enemies of Islam.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The leader of the uprising, Juhayman al-Otaybi, read out a list of grievances, as he accused the House of Saud of being corrupt and degenerate, listing by name a number of Saudi princes who were engaged in dubious business dealings and/or who drank alcohol.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Saudi Army recaptured the Grand Mosque, and the surviving "renegades", as the rebels were labelled, were executed.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In Algeria, the "oil shock" led to the establishment of a welfare state where none had existed previously.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The lower oil prices of the 1980s along with cutbacks and the belief that the FLN regime was corrupt helped cause the riots of October 1988 against the FLN regime, that killed at least 500 people.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The riots were largely caused by the fact that the low oil prices had forced the Algerian state to end many of its more generous social policies between 1986 and 1988, leading to an unemployment rate of 30% by 1988, along with the knowledge that the FLN regime had stolen millions.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In the aftermath of the October riots, President Chadli Bendjedid began a transition to democracy.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The first free elections in Algeria in January 1992 were won by the Islamist FIS, which led to a military coup and an outbreak of a civil war that killed hundreds of thousands of Algerians.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] OPEC-member states raised the prospect of nationalization of oil company holdings.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Most notably, Saudi Arabia nationalized Aramco in 1980 under the leadership of Saudi oil minister Ahmed Zaki Yamani.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] As other OPEC nations followed suit, the cartel's income soared.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Saudi Arabia undertook a series of ambitious five-year development plans.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The biggest began in 1980, funded at $250 billion.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Other cartel members also undertook major economic development programs.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Control of oil became known as the "oil weapon".
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] It came in the form of an embargo and production cutbacks from the Arab states.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The weapon was aimed at the United States, Great Britain, Canada, Japan and the Netherlands.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] These target governments perceived that the intent was to push them towards a more pro-Arab position.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] However, the affected countries did not undertake dramatic policy changes.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The risk that the Middle East could become another superpower confrontation with the USSR was of more concern to Washington than oil.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Further, interest groups and government agencies more worried about energy were no match for Kissinger's dominance.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The embargo had a negative influence on the US economy, causing immediate demands to address the threats to US energy security.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On an international level, the price increases changed competitive positions in many industries, such as automobiles.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Macroeconomic problems consisted of both inflationary and deflationary impacts.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The embargo left oil companies searching for new ways to increase oil supplies, even in rugged terrain such as the Arctic.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Finding oil and developing new fields usually required five to 10 years before significant production.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The average US retail price of a gallon of regular gasoline rose 43% from 38.5¢ in May 1973 to 55.1¢ in June 1974.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] State governments asked citizens not to put up Christmas lights.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Oregon banned Christmas and commercial lighting altogether.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Politicians called for a national gasoline rationing program.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Nixon asked gasoline retailers to voluntarily not sell gasoline on Saturday nights or Sundays.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] 90% of gas station owners complied, which produced long lines of motorists wanting to fill up their cars while they still could.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The "oil shock" provided considerable impetus to the American nuclear industry as a way to achieve "energy independence" from the Middle East.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On 7 November 1973, Nixon in an address to Congress called for Project Independence to make the United States self-sufficient in energy by 1980, which called for a massive investment in the nuclear industry.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Nixon envisioned nuclear energy as more economical, and was encouraged by the enthusiasm of many officials who saw nuclear energy as the technology of the future.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By the late 1960s, a lively environmentalist movement had emerged in the United States, and the Project Independence nuclear program was the subject of much debate in both the media and Congress.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The ensuing debates revealed that many of the claims made for nuclear power underestimated the true costs of nuclear reactors.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Equally problematic was where to safety store the spent nuclear rods that emitted a toxic level of radioactivity for centuries afterward, in a cost-effective manner.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The issue of the spent nuclear rods was especially difficult because of NIMBYism, where communities proved unwilling to accept a storage place for the inevitable by-product of nuclear power, the spent nuclear rods, with the demand that the government find some other community to store the rods.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Many of the nuclear reactors ordered in 1973 were cancelled due to cost overruns, while over 100 nuclear plants were shut down as uneconomical over the next 10 years.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Unlike nations that tried to use nuclear power as a way for energy independence such as France and Sweden, the United States had substantial reserves of its own oil, which weakened the case for nuclear power in the ensuring debates.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By 1989, only 18% of American energy came from nuclear power plants, which was a fraction of what Project Independence had envisioned in 1973.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil shock led to anti-Arab feelings becoming common.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Cartoons published in American newspapers during the oil shock depicted Arabs as disgusting, ugly, obese, corrupt and greedy.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In the cartoons, the long hooked Semitic noses that had traditionally been featured in anti-Jewish cartoons were applied to the Arab sheiks as a way to illustrate their supposed greed.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] American public opinion did not see the use of the "oil weapon" as due to politics, and tended to explain the embargo as only due to the excessive greed of King Faisal and the other Arab leaders, hence the use of the hooked Semitic nose in the cartoons as a sort of shorthand for insatiable greed.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Soviet Union was not a beneficiary of the oil crisis.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The crisis prompted the USSR to raise energy prices within the Council on Mutual Economic Assistance (CMEA).
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The embargo was not uniform across Western Europe.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Of the nine members of the European Economic Community (EEC), the Netherlands faced a complete embargo.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By contrast Britain and France received almost uninterrupted supplies.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] That was their reward for refusing to allow the US to use their airfields and stopping arms and supplies to both the Arabs and the Israelis.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The other six EEC nations faced partial cutbacks.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The UK had traditionally been an ally of Israel, and Harold Wilson's government supported the Israelis during the Six-Day War.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] His successor, Ted Heath, reversed this policy in 1970, calling for Israel to withdraw to its pre-1967 borders.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The devalued franc made imports more expensive for French consumers, which encouraged them to buy French products, while making French products cheaper abroad.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] France was entirely dependent upon imported oil, through French companies continued to lease the oil concessions in Algeria until 1971.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The low price of oil internationally compensated to a certain extent for the higher price of oil caused by the devaluation.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The devalued franc ensured that the dramatic price increases caused by the oil shock hit the French economy especially hard in 1973.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The UK, Germany, Italy, Switzerland and Norway banned flying, driving and boating on Sundays.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Sweden rationed gasoline and heating oil.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Netherlands imposed prison sentences for those who used more than their ration of electricity.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The EEC was unable to achieve a common policy during the first month of the embargo.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] It issued a statement on November 6, after the embargo and price rises had begun.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] It was widely viewed as pro-Arab, supporting the Franco-British line on the war.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] OPEC duly lifted its embargo from all EEC members.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The other European states did not rally in defense of the Dutch who were left to fend for themselves and instead reached bilateral deals with Saudi Arabia, Iraq and Iran.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Faced with a recession, there was a tendency within the EEC nations to turn inwards away from European integration.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The price rises had a much greater impact in Europe than the embargo.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The crisis retarded the movement towards European economic integration which had been gathering pace ever since the EEC, now the European Union, had been founded in 1957.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In 1973, the German historian Jens-Uwe Wunderlich wrote that attempts to finish off the European common market came to a "complete standstill" in 1973 and it was not until 1977 that movement towards creating the common market resumed.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In particular, the oil shock increased the appeal of nuclear energy as a way to achieve energy independence from the turbulent Middle East.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Starting in March 1974 with the "Energy Plan" introduced by the premier Pierre Messmer, the French state made a massive investment in nuclear energy.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By the 1990s, 80% of all of France's energy came from nuclear plants.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The North Sea oil fields, which were discovered in 1969, did not start to be exploited until 1975, making the United Kingdom entirely dependent upon imported oil in 1973.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The way that world oil prices quadrupled in late 1973 had a very adverse impact on the British economy,.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In a series of speeches in December 1973, the Prime Minister Edward Heath warned that because of the oil shock that the British economy was going into recession and the British people should expect economic austerity.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Heath offered the coal miners a 7% wage increase, which was rejected as insufficient by the miners who went on strike.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Through not subjected to the embargo, the UK faced an energy crisis of its own—a series of strikes by coal miners and railroad workers over the winter of 1973–74 became a major factor in the defeat of Heath's Conservative government in the February 1974 general elections.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The new Labour government told the British to heat only one room in their houses over the winter.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Labour government of Harold Wilson settled the strike by giving the coal miners a 35% pay increase.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Japan was hard hit, since it imported 90% of its oil from the Middle East.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] It had a stockpile good for 55 days, and another 20-day supply was en route.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Facing its most serious crisis since 1945, the government ordered a 10% cut in the consumption of industrial oil and electricity.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In December 1973, it ordered an immediate 20% cut in oil use and electric power to Japan's major industries, and cutbacks in leisure automobile usage.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Economist predicted the growth rate would plunge from 5% annually, down to zero or even negative territory.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Seeking to take advantage of the crisis, Japanese business called on the government to relax its controls on air pollution and water pollution.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Moscow tried to take advantage by promising energy assistance if Japan renounced its claim to the Kurile Islands.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Instead it made $3.3 billion of dollars in loans to the Arab states and called on Israel to step back.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Japan's defensive strategy was explained to Kissinger when he met with top leaders in Tokyo in November 1973.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In the long run Japan never wavered in its determination to maintain very strong close ties to the United States, while in self-defense briefly providing the Arab powers with the rhetoric they demanded in return for resuming oil shipments in early 1974.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] To assure future oil flows, Japan added suppliers outside of the Middle East, invested in nuclear power, imposed conservation measures, and provided funding for Arab governments and the Palestinians.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The crisis was a major factor in the long-run shift of Japan's economy away from oil-intensive industries.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Japanese auto makers benefited from the crisis.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The jump in gasoline prices helped their small, fuel-efficient models to gain market share from the "gas-guzzling" Detroit competition.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] This triggered a drop in US sales of American cars that lasted into the 1980s.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil crisis contributed to the poor state of the Indian economy and played a role in Indira Gandhi's decision to impose The Emergency, a dictatorship.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The state led a push for coal as an energy source, even though there were reservations about its adverse environmental effects.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil shock destroyed the economy of South Vietnam.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] A spokesman for President Nguyễn Văn Thiệu admitted in a TV interview that the government was being "overwhelmed" by the inflation caused by the oil shock.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] An American businessman living in Saigon stated after the oil shock, that attempting to make money in South Vietnam was "like making love to a corpse".
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In December 1973, Vietcong sappers attacked and destroyed the petroleum depot of Nha Be, further depleting fuel sources.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By the summer of 1974, the US embassy in Saigon reported that morale in the ARVN (Army of the Republic of Vietnam) had fallen to dangerously low levels and it was uncertain how much more longer South Vietnam would last.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] As inflation eroded the value of the South Vietnamese *đồng*, it became common by the summer of 1974 to see ARVN soldiers and their families begging in the streets for food.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In December 1974, the North Vietnamese PAVN (People's Army of Vietnam) launched an offensive in the Central Highlands that was far more successful than expected, due to the ARVN's low morale and weak resistance.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On March 1, 1975, the PAVN launched a major offensive that quickly overran the Central Highlands.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Following their victory in the Central Highlands, the North Vietnamese launched the "Ho Chi Minh Campaign" that captured Saigon on April 30, 1975.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Three of the nations targeted by the embargo were located in southern Africa or had colonies there.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Portugal which ruled the colonies of Angola, Portuguese Guiana (modern Guinea-Bissau), and Portuguese East Africa (modern Mozambique) had fighting colonial wars in all of its African colonies since the 1960s with Angola being the first to rise up in 1961.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Angola is rich in oil, which protected Portugal from the worse of the embargo.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] But the economic stability of the *Estado Novo* regime was damaged by the worldwide inflation, which help cause the Carnation Revolution which toppled the *Estado Novo* regime in April 1974 and led to the restoration of democracy.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Portugal granted independence to all of its colonies except for Macau in 1975.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The British historian Rob Skinner wrote the embargo had a "significant impact" on the South African economy.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The inflationary rise in commodity prices increased the input costs of South African manufacturing, making South African manufactured goods uncompetitive on the world market.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The rise in the price of gold as a hedge against inflation (South Africa has the world's largest gold mines) caused the *rand* to increase in value, which caused further problems for South African manufacturing.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The strategy pursued by the National Party government since 1948 of sponsoring the industrialization of South Africa was derailed by the oil shock, with what Skinner described as "important social and political consequences" for the *apartheid* regime.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Soweto uprising of 1976 was at least in part caused by anger at the high unemployment rate in the black South African community.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Even worse hit than South Africa was Rhodesia (modern Zimbabwe), where oil was already expensive as the white supremacist government of Rhodesia had been under United Nations sanctions since 1965, and thus the smugglers who sold Rhodesia oil charged a premium for their services.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The premium charged by the "sanctions busters" such as Iran increased after the embargo, which threw the Rhodesian economy into recession.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Despite the United Nations sanctions, Rhodesia was a major exporter of chrome, steel and tobacco with the United States exempting "strategical" Rhodesian products such as chrome from the sanctions.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The global recession of 1973–1975 proved more effective than the United Nations in ending the global demand for Rhodesian products, which made the Rhodesian recession especially severe.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Unlike South Africa, which had a sizable and long-standing white population, the white population of Rhodesia was much smaller and more recent.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Rhodesia depended considerably more than South Africa on white immigration to provide enough soldiers for its army, while most of the Rhodesian whites had only arrived in the 1950s and did not have very deep roots in the country.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The white flight caused by the recession put the Rhodesian Army at a major disadvantage in its war against the black guerrillas.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The war cost the Rhodesian government one million Rhodesian dollars per day by 1975, and the costs of the war threatened to bankrupt Rhodesia.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1979, Rhodesia signed the Lancaster House Agreement, which led to Black majority rule in 1980.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Price controls exacerbated the crisis in the US.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The system limited the price of "old oil", that which had already been discovered, while allowing newly discovered oil to be sold at a higher price, to encourage investment.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As a result, old oil was withdrawn from the market, creating greater scarcity.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The rule also discouraged development of alternative energies.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The rule had been intended to promote oil exploration.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Scarcity was addressed by rationing, as in many countries.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Motorists faced long lines at gas stations beginning in summer 1972 and increasing by summer 1973.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] A sign of the change caused by the crisis was that in 1974 the Exxon oil company replaced the General Motors corporation to be the largest corporation in the world, as measured by gross sales revenues.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Simon as the first Administrator of the Federal Energy Office, a short-term organization created to coordinate the response to the embargo.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Simon allocated states the same amount of domestic oil for 1974 that each had consumed in 1972, which worked for states whose populations were not increasing.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In other states, lines at gasoline stations were common.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The American Automobile Association reported that in the last week of February 1974, 20% of American gasoline stations had no fuel.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Odd–even rationing allowed vehicles with license plates having an odd number as the last digit, or a vanity license plate, to buy gas only on odd-numbered days of the month.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Others could buy only on even-numbered days.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In some states, a three-color flag system was used to denote gasoline availability at service stations—green for unrationed availability, yellow for restricted/rationed sales, and red for out of stock.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Rationing led to violent incidents, when truck drivers chose to strike for two days in December 1973 over the limited supplies that Simon had allocated for their industry.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In Pennsylvania and Ohio, non-striking truckers were shot at by striking truckers.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In Arkansas, trucks of non-strikers were attacked with bombs.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] America had controlled the price of natural gas since the 1950s.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] With the inflation of the 1970s, the price was too low to encourage the search for new reserves.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] America's natural gas reserves dwindled from 237 trillion in 1974 to 203 trillion in 1978.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The price controls were not changed, despite president Gerald Ford's repeated requests to Congress.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] To help reduce consumption, in 1974 a national maximum speed limit of 55 mph (89 km/h) was imposed through the Emergency Highway Energy Conservation Act.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Development of the Strategic Petroleum Reserve began in 1975, and in 1977 the cabinet-level Department of Energy was created, followed by the National Energy Act of 1978.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In November 1995, President Bill Clinton signed the National Highway Designation Act, ending the federal 55 mph speed limit, which allowed states to restore their prior maximum speed limit.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Year-round daylight saving time was implemented from January 6, 1974, to October 27, 1975, with a break between October 27, 1974, and February 23, 1975, when the country observed standard time.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Parents complained that it forced many children to travel to school before sunrise.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The crisis prompted a call to conserve energy, most notably a campaign by the Advertising Council using the tagline "Don't Be Fuelish".
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Many newspapers carried advertisements featuring cut-outs that could be attached to light switches, reading "Last Out, Lights Out: Don't Be Fuelish".
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Although not regulated by the new legislation, auto racing groups voluntarily began conserving.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1974, NASCAR reduced all race distances by 10%; the 24 Hours of Daytona and the 12 Hours of Sebring race were cancelled.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1975, the Energy Policy and Conservation Act was passed, leading to the creation of the Corporate Average Fuel Economy (CAFE) standards that required improved fuel economy for cars and light trucks.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1976, Congress created the Weatherization Assistance Program to help low-income homeowners and renters reduce their demand for heating and cooling through better insulation.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1980, domestic luxury cars with a 130-inch (3.3 m) wheelbase and gross weights averaging 4,500 pounds (2,041 kg) were no longer made.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The automakers had begun phasing out the traditional front engine/rear-wheel drive layout in compact cars in favor of lighter front engine/front-wheel drive designs.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] A higher percentage of cars offered more efficient four-cylinder engines.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Domestic auto makers also began offering more fuel efficient diesel powered passenger cars as well.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The energy crisis led to greater interest in renewable energy, nuclear power and domestic fossil fuels.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 2013, Peter Grossman opined that American energy policies after the crisis became and remained dominated by crisis-mentality thinking, promoting expensive quick fixes and single-shot solutions that ignore market and technology realities.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] He wrote that instead of providing stable rules that support basic research while leaving plenty of scope for entrepreneurship and innovation, Congresses and presidents repeatedly backed policies which promised politically expedient solutions whose true prospects were doubtful.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The Brazilian government implemented its Proálcool (pro-alcohol) project in 1975 that mixed ethanol with gasoline for automotive fuel.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Israel was one of the few countries unaffected by the embargo, since it could extract sufficient oil from the Sinai.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] But to supplement Israel's over-taxed power grid, Harry Zvi Tabor, the father of Israel's solar industry, developed the prototype for a solar water heater now used in over 90% of Israeli homes.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Western central banks decided to sharply cut interest rates to encourage growth, deciding that inflation was a secondary concern.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Although this was the orthodox macroeconomic prescription at the time, the resulting stagflation surprised economists and central bankers.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The policy is now considered by some to have deepened and lengthened the adverse effects of the embargo.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Recent research claims that in the period after 1985 the economy became more resilient to energy price increases.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The price shock created large current account deficits in oil-importing economies.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] A petrodollar recycling mechanism was created, through which OPEC surplus funds were channeled through the capital markets to the West to finance the current account deficits.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The functioning of this mechanism required the relaxation of capital controls in oil-importing economies.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] It marked the beginning of an exponential growth of Western capital markets.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In the United States in 1974, seven of the 15 top Fortune 500 companies were oil companies, falling to four in 2014.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The crisis had a major impact on international relations and created a rift within NATO.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Some European nations and Japan sought to disassociate themselves from United States foreign policy in the Middle East to avoid being targeted by the boycott.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Arab oil producers linked any future policy changes to peace between the belligerents.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] To address this, the Nixon Administration began multilateral negotiations with the combatants.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] They arranged for Israel to pull back from the Sinai Peninsula and the Golan Heights.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By January 18, 1974, US Secretary of State Henry Kissinger had negotiated an Israeli troop withdrawal from parts of the Sinai Peninsula.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The promise of a negotiated settlement between Israel and Syria was enough to convince Arab oil producers to lift the embargo in March 1974. and again during the 1979 energy crisis.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] America's Cold War policies suffered a major blow from the embargo.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] They had focused on China and the Soviet Union, but the latent challenge to US hegemony coming from the Third World became evident.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 2004, declassified documents revealed that the US was so distraught by the rise in oil prices and being challenged by underdeveloped countries that they briefly considered military action to forcibly seize Middle Eastern oilfields in late 1973.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Western Europe began switching from pro-Israel to more pro-Arab policies.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] This change strained the Western alliance.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The US, which imported only 12% of its oil from the Middle East (compared with 80% for the Europeans and over 90% for Japan), remained staunchly committed to Israel.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The percentage of US oil which comes from the nations bordering the Persian Gulf remained steady over the decades, with a figure of a little more than 10% in 2008.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] With the embargo in place, many developed countries altered their policies regarding the Arab-Israeli conflict.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] These included the UK, which refused to allow the United States to use British bases and Cyprus to airlift resupplies to Israel, along with the rest of the members of the European Community.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Canada shifted towards a more pro-Arab position after displeasure was expressed towards Canada's mostly neutral position.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] "On the other hand, after the embargo the Canadian government moved quickly indeed toward the Arab position, despite its low dependence on Middle Eastern oil".
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Although lacking historical connections to the Middle East, Japan was the country most dependent on Arab oil.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] 71% of its imported oil came from the Middle East in 1970.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] On November 7, 1973, the Saudi and Kuwaiti governments declared Japan a "nonfriendly" country, to encourage it to change its noninvolvement policy.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] It received a 5% production cut in December, causing a panic.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] On November 22, Japan issued a statement "asserting that Israel should withdraw from all of the 1967 territories, advocating Palestinian self-determination, and threatening to reconsider its policy toward Israel if Israel refused to accept these preconditions".
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By December 25, Japan was considered an Arab-friendly state.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The oil embargo was announced roughly one month after a right-wing military coup in Chile led by General Augusto Pinochet toppled socialist president Salvador Allende on September 11, 1973.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The response of the Nixon administration was to propose doubling arms sales.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As a consequence, an opposing Latin American bloc was organized and financed in part by Venezuelan oil revenues, which quadrupled between 1970 and 1975.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The oil shock disrupted the status quo relationships between Arab countries and the US and USSR.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] At the time, Egypt, Syria and Iraq were allied with the USSR.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Saudi Arabia, Turkey and Iran, plus Israel, aligned with the US.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Vacillations in alignment often resulted in greater support from the respective superpowers.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] When Anwar Sadat became president of Egypt in 1970, he dismissed Soviet specialists in Egypt and reoriented towards the US.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Concerns over economic domination from increased Soviet oil production turned into fears of military aggression after the 1979 Soviet invasion of Afghanistan, a major turning point in Cold War geopolitics.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Persian Gulf states turned toward the US for security guarantees against Soviet military action, coming at a time marked by increased American weapons sales, technology, and outright military presence to various US-allied nations.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Saudi Arabia and Iran became increasingly dependent on American security assurances to manage both external and internal threats, including increased military competition between them over increased oil revenues.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Both states were competing for preeminence in the Persian Gulf, and using increased revenues to fund expanded militaries.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1979, Saudi arms purchases from the US were five times larger than Israel's.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Saudi Arabia is a near-absolute monarchy, an Arabic speaking country, and has a Sunni Muslim majority, while Persian speaking Iran since 1979 is an Islamist theocracy with a Shiite Muslim majority, which explains the current hostility between Saudi Arabia and Iran.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The oil crisis sent a signal to the auto industry globally, which changed many aspects of production and usage for decades to come.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] After World War II, most West European countries taxed motor fuel to limit imports, and as a result most cars made in Europe were smaller and more economical than their American counterparts.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By the late 1960s, increasing incomes supported rising car sizes.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The oil crisis pushed West European car buyers away from larger, less economical cars.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The most notable result of this transition was the rise in popularity of compact hatchbacks.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The only notable small hatchbacks built in Western Europe before the oil crisis were the Peugeot 104, Renault 5 and Fiat 127.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By the end of the decade, the market had expanded with the introduction of the Ford Fiesta, Opel Kadett (sold as the Vauxhall Astra in Great Britain), Chrysler Sunbeam and Citroën Visa.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Buyers looking for larger cars were increasingly drawn to medium-sized hatchbacks.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Virtually unknown in Europe in 1973, by the end of the decade they were gradually replacing sedans as the mainstay of this sector.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Between 1973 and 1980, medium-sized hatchbacks were launched across Europe: the Chrysler/Simca Horizon, Fiat Ritmo (Strada in the UK), Ford Escort MK3, Renault 14, Volvo 340 / 360, Opel Kadett, and Volkswagen Golf.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] These cars were considerably more economical than the traditional saloons they were replacing, and attracted buyers who traditionally bought larger vehicles.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Some 15 years after the oil crisis, hatchbacks dominated most European small and medium car markets, and had gained a substantial share of the large family car market.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Before the energy crisis, large, heavy, and powerful cars were popular.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1971, the standard engine in a Chevrolet Caprice was a 400-cubic inch (6.5 liter) V8.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The wheelbase of this car was 121.5 inches (3,090 mm), and *Motor Trend*'s 1972 road test of the similar Chevrolet Impala achieved no more than 15 highway miles per gallon.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In the 15 years prior to the 1973 oil crisis, gasoline prices in the US had lagged well behind inflation.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The crisis reduced the demand for large cars.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Japanese imports became mass-market leaders with unibody construction and front-wheel drive, which became de facto standards.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] From Europe, the Volkswagen Beetle, the Volkswagen Fastback, the Renault 8, the Renault LeCar, and the Fiat Brava were successful.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Detroit responded with the Ford Pinto, the Ford Maverick, the Chevrolet Vega, the Chevrolet Nova, the Plymouth Valiant and the Plymouth Volaré.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] American Motors sold its homegrown Gremlin, Hornet and Pacer models.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] A decade after the 1973 oil crisis, Honda, Toyota and Nissan, affected by the 1981 voluntary export restraints, opened US assembly plants and established their luxury divisions (Acura, Lexus and Infiniti, respectively) to distinguish themselves from their mass-market brands.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Compact trucks were introduced, such as the Toyota Hilux and the Datsun Truck, followed by the Mazda Truck (sold as the Ford Courier), and the Isuzu-built Chevrolet LUV.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Mitsubishi rebranded its Forte as the Dodge D-50 a few years after the oil crisis.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Mazda, Mitsubishi and Isuzu had joint partnerships with Ford, Chrysler, and GM, respectively.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Later, the American makers introduced their domestic replacements (Ford Ranger, Dodge Dakota and the Chevrolet S10/GMC S-15), ending their captive import policy.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] An increase in imported cars into North America forced General Motors, Ford and Chrysler to introduce smaller and fuel-efficient models for domestic sales.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The Dodge Omni / Plymouth Horizon from Chrysler, the Ford Fiesta and the Chevrolet Chevette all had four-cylinder engines and room for at least four passengers by the late 1970s.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1985, the average American vehicle moved 17.4 miles per gallon, compared to 13.5 in 1970.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The improvements stayed, even though the price of a barrel of oil remained constant at $12 from 1974 to 1979.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Sales of large sedans for most makes, except Chrysler products, recovered within two model years of the 1973 crisis.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The Cadillac DeVille and Fleetwood, Buick Electra, Oldsmobile 98, Lincoln Continental, Mercury Marquis, and various other luxury oriented sedans became popular again in the mid-1970s.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The only full-size models that did not recover were lower price models such as the Chevrolet Bel Air and Ford Galaxie 500.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Slightly smaller models such as the Oldsmobile Cutlass, Chevrolet Monte Carlo, Ford Thunderbird and various others sold well.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Economical imports succeeded alongside heavy, expensive vehicles.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1976, Toyota sold 346,920 cars (average weight around 2,100 lbs), while Cadillac sold 309,139 cars (average weight around 5,000 lbs).
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Federal safety standards, such as NHTSA Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standard 215 (pertaining to safety bumpers), and compacts like the 1974 Mustang I were a prelude to the DOT "downsize" revision of vehicle categories.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1977, GM's full-sized cars reflected the crisis.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1979, virtually all "full-size" American cars had shrunk, featuring smaller engines and smaller outside dimensions.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Chrysler ended production of their full-sized luxury sedans at the end of the 1981 model year, moving instead to a full front-wheel drive lineup for 1982, except for the M-body Dodge Diplomat/Plymouth Gran Fury and Chrysler New Yorker Fifth Avenue sedans.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] OPEC soon lost its preeminent position, and in 1981, its production was surpassed by that of other countries.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Additionally, its own member nations were divided.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Saudi Arabia, trying to recover market share, increased production, pushing prices down, shrinking or eliminating profits for high-cost producers.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The world price, which had peaked during the 1979 energy crisis at nearly $40 per barrel, decreased during the 1980s to less than $10 per barrel.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Adjusted for inflation, oil briefly fell back to pre-1973 levels.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] This "sale" price was a windfall for oil-importing nations, both developing and developed.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] During the Iran–Iraq War of 1980–1988, the stated war aim of Iran was to overthrow the Baath regime in Iraq.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As a consequence, Saudi Arabia and the other Arab Gulf states leaned in a very pro-Iraqi neutrality during the war.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As a part of its policy of supporting Iraq, Saudi Arabia pumped out oil in massive quantities to lower the price as a way of hurting Iran's economy.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The low price of oil also hurt Iraq's economy, which forced Iraq to borrow massive sums of money, putting Iraq deeply into debt.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In contrast, Iran refused to borrow any money because of its refusal to pay interest on any loans, and paid the costs of the war directly from the sale of its oil.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Iran's revenue from the sale of oil went from $20 billion US dollars per year in 1982 to $5 billion US dollars per year by 1988, which pushed Iran to the verge of bankruptcy and forced Iran to make peace with Iraq later in 1988.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] During the war, the Iranian delegation at OPEC tried very hard to have the group cut production to raise prices, but were blocked by the other delegations led by the Saudi delegation, who insisted on more oil production.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The embargo encouraged new venues for energy exploration, including Alaska, the North Sea, the Caspian Sea, and the Caucasus.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Exploration in the Caspian Basin and Siberia became profitable.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Cooperation changed into a far more adversarial relationship as the USSR increased its production.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1980, the Soviet Union had become the world's largest producer.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Part of the decline in prices and economic and geopolitical power of OPEC came from the move to alternative energy sources.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] OPEC had relied on price inelasticity to maintain high consumption, but had underestimated the extent to which conservation and other sources of supply would eventually reduce demand.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Electricity generation from nuclear power and natural gas, home heating from natural gas, and ethanol-blended gasoline all reduced the demand for oil.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The drop in prices presented a serious problem for oil-exporting countries in northern Europe and the Persian Gulf.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Heavily populated, impoverished countries, whose economies were largely dependent on oil—including Mexico, Nigeria, Algeria, and Libya—did not prepare for a market reversal that left them in sometimes desperate situations.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] When reduced demand and increased production glutted the world market in the mid-1980s, oil prices plummeted and the cartel lost its unity.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Mexico (a non-member), Nigeria, and Venezuela, whose economies had expanded in the 1970s, faced near-bankruptcy, and even Saudi Arabian economic power was significantly weakened.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The divisions within OPEC made concerted action more difficult.
[src:california-gold-rush/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As of 2015, OPEC has never approached its earlier dominance.
[src:california-gold-rush/1976-sterling-crisis] The **1976 sterling crisis** was a currency crisis in the United Kingdom.
[src:california-gold-rush/1976-sterling-crisis] Inflation (at close to 25% in 1975, causing high bond yields and borrowing costs), a balance-of-payments deficit, a public-spending deficit, and the 1973 oil crisis were contributors.
[src:california-gold-rush/1976-sterling-crisis] The origins of the crisis have been attributed to the 1972 Conservative "dash for growth" budget initiating the inflation cycle.
[src:california-gold-rush/1976-sterling-crisis] James Callaghan's Labour government had to borrow $3.9 billion (equivalent to $22.1 billion in 2025 dollars) from the International Monetary Fund (IMF), while implementing significant spending cuts, with the intention of maintaining the value of sterling.
[src:california-gold-rush/1976-sterling-crisis] At the time this was the largest loan ever to have been requested from the IMF.
[src:california-gold-rush/1976-sterling-crisis] Initiation of the inflationary cycle is traced to Anthony Barber's 1972 budget which was designed to return the Conservatives to power in an election expected in 1974 or 1975.
[src:california-gold-rush/1976-sterling-crisis] This budget led to a brief period of growth known as "The Barber Boom," followed by a wage-price spiral, high inflation and currency depreciation, culminating in the 1976 sterling crisis.
[src:california-gold-rush/1976-sterling-crisis] Barber was forced to introduce anti-inflation measures, along with a Price Commission and a Pay Board.
[src:california-gold-rush/1976-sterling-crisis] The Conservatives lost the February 1974 general election (and the subsequent election held the same October) to Harold Wilson's Labour Party.
[src:california-gold-rush/1976-sterling-crisis] After the defeat of the 1976 public expenditure white paper in the House of Commons in March 1976 and the Bank of England withdrew temporarily from the foreign exchange market, Harold Wilson resigned as prime minister and was replaced by James Callaghan in April.
[src:california-gold-rush/1976-sterling-crisis] Many investors became convinced sterling would soon lose value due to inflation.
[src:california-gold-rush/1976-sterling-crisis] By June 1976, the pound had reached a record low against the dollar.
[src:california-gold-rush/1976-sterling-crisis] In 1967, the Suez Canal closed down for eight years following the Six-Day War of that year, when Israel took and occupied the Sinai Peninsula for 15 years.
[src:california-gold-rush/1976-sterling-crisis] That triggered the 1967 Oil Embargo, which only lasted a few months.
[src:california-gold-rush/1976-sterling-crisis] In 1966, the year before it closed, 20% of all world oil cargo tonnage passed through the canal, with most of it heading north for Europe.
[src:california-gold-rush/1976-sterling-crisis] In 1973, the Yom Kippur War was fought, with Egypt crossing the Suez Canal aiming to take back the Sinai Peninsula from Israel.
[src:california-gold-rush/1976-sterling-crisis] This triggered the 1973 oil crisis and embargo.
[src:california-gold-rush/1976-sterling-crisis] Britain was an ally to Israel during the Arab–Israeli conflict.
[src:california-gold-rush/1976-sterling-crisis] The oil crisis presented a severe economic shock to Britain, which it was ill-placed to withstand.
[src:california-gold-rush/1976-sterling-crisis] Only half of the loan was actually drawn by the British government and it was repaid by 4 May 1979, the day after the general election.
[src:california-gold-rush/1976-sterling-crisis] Denis Healey, the Chancellor of the Exchequer at the time, went on to state that the main reason the loan had to be requested was that public sector borrowing requirement figures provided by the Treasury were grossly overstated.
[src:california-gold-rush/1976-sterling-crisis] The IMF loan meant that the United Kingdom's economy could be stabilised whilst drastic budget cuts were implemented.
[src:california-gold-rush/1976-sterling-crisis] Despite the security provided by the loan, the Labour Party had already begun separating into social democratic and more socialist camps, causing bitter rows inside the party and with the trades unions.
[src:california-gold-rush/1976-sterling-crisis] The sterling crisis and IMF bailout contributed to Margaret Thatcher's 1979 Conservative victory.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] The **California gold rush** (1848–1855) was a gold rush in California, which began on January 24, 1848, when gold was found by James W.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Marshall at Sutter's Mill in Coloma, California.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] The news of gold brought approximately 300,000 people from the rest of the United States and abroad to California, which had recently been conquered from Mexico.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] The sudden influx of gold into the money supply reinvigorated the American economy; the sudden population increase allowed California to grow rapidly into statehood in the Compromise of 1850.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] The gold rush had severe effects on Native Californians and accelerated the Native American population's decline from factors including disease, starvation, and according to certain sources, acts of unprovoked aggression.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] The effects of the gold rush were substantial.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] The arrival of large numbers of "forty-niners" (referring to 1849, the peak year for gold rush immigration) led to significant conflict between the newcomers and indigenous people, eventually resulting in whole tribes being displaced in some cases.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Outside of California, the first to arrive were from Oregon, Hawaii, and Latin America in late 1848.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Of the approximately 300,000 people who came to California during the gold rush, about half arrived by sea and half came overland on the California Trail and the California Road; forty-niners often faced substantial hardships on the trip.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] While most of the newly arrived were Americans, the gold rush attracted thousands from Latin America, Europe, Australia, and China.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Agriculture and ranching expanded throughout the state to meet the needs of the settlers.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] San Francisco grew from a small settlement of about 200 residents in 1846 to a boomtown of about 36,000 by 1852.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Roads, churches, schools and other towns were built throughout California.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] In 1849, a state constitution was written.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] The new constitution was adopted by referendum vote; the future state's interim first governor and legislature were chosen.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] In September 1850, California achieved statehood.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] At the beginning of the gold rush, there was no law regarding property rights in the goldfields and a system of "staking claims" was developed.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Prospectors retrieved the gold from streams and riverbeds using simple techniques, such as panning.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Although mining caused environmental harm, more sophisticated methods of gold recovery were developed and later adopted around the world.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] New methods of transportation developed as steamships came into regular service.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] By 1869, railroads were built from California to the eastern United States.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] At its peak, technological advances reached a point where significant financing was required, increasing the proportion of gold companies to individual miners.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Gold worth tens of billions of today's US dollars was recovered, which led to great wealth for a few, though many who participated in the California gold rush earned little more than they had started with.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Gold was discovered in California as early as March 9, 1842, at Rancho San Francisco, in the mountains north of present-day Los Angeles.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Californian native Francisco Lopez was searching for stray horses and stopped on the bank of a small creek (in today's Placerita Canyon), about 3 miles (4.8 km) east of present-day Newhall, and about 35 miles (56 km) northwest of Los Angeles.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] While the horses grazed, Lopez dug up some wild onions and found a small gold nugget in the roots among the bulbs.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Lopez took the gold to authorities who confirmed its worth.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Lopez and others began to search for other streambeds with gold deposits in the area.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] They found several in the northeastern section of the forest, within present-day Ventura County.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] In November, some of the gold was sent to the U.S.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Mint, but otherwise attracted little notice.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] In 1843, Lopez found gold in San Feliciano Canyon near his first discovery.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Mexican miners from Sonora worked the placer deposits until 1846.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Minor finds of gold in California were also made by Mission Indians prior to 1848.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] The friars instructed them to keep its location secret to avoid a gold rush.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] In January 1847, nine months into the Mexican–American War, the Treaty of Cahuenga was signed, leading to the resolution of the military conflict in Alta California (Upper California).
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Marshall found shiny metal in the tailrace of a lumber mill he was building for Sacramento pioneer John Sutter—known as Sutter's Mill, near Coloma on the American River.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Marshall brought what he found to Sutter, and the two privately tested the metal.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] After the tests showed that it was gold, Sutter expressed dismay, wanting to keep the news quiet because he feared what would happen to his plans for an agricultural empire if there were a gold rush in the region.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] The Mexican–American War ended on May 30 with the ratification of the Treaty of Guadalupe Hidalgo, which formally transferred California to the United States.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Having sworn all concerned at the mill to secrecy, in February 1848, Sutter sent Charles Bennett to Monterey to meet with Colonel Mason, the chief U.S. official in California, to secure the mineral rights of the land where the mill stood.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Bennett was not to tell anyone of the discovery of gold, but when he stopped at Benicia, he heard talk about the discovery of coal near Mount Diablo, and he blurted out the discovery of gold.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] He continued to San Francisco, where again, he could not keep the secret.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] At Monterey, Mason declined to make any judgement of title to lands and mineral rights, and Bennett for the third time revealed the gold discovery.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] By March 1848, rumors of the discovery were confirmed by San Francisco newspaper publisher and merchant Samuel Brannan.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Brannan hurriedly set up a store to sell gold prospecting supplies, and he walked through the streets of San Francisco, holding aloft a vial of gold, shouting "Gold!
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] On August 19, 1848, the *New York Herald* was the first major newspaper on the East Coast to report the discovery of gold.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] On December 5, 1848, US president James K.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Polk confirmed the discovery of gold in an address to Congress.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] As a result, individuals seeking to benefit from the gold rush—later called the "forty-niners"—began moving to the Gold Country of California or "Mother Lode" from other countries and from other parts of the United States.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] As Sutter had feared, his business plans were ruined after his workers left in search of gold, and squatters took over his land and stole his crops and cattle.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] San Francisco had been a tiny settlement before the rush began.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] When residents learned about the discovery, it at first became a ghost town of abandoned ships and businesses, but then boomed as merchants and new people arrived.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] The population of San Francisco increased quickly from about 1,000 in 1848 to 25,000 full-time residents by 1850.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Miners lived in tents, wood shanties, or deck cabins removed from abandoned ships.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] There were no churches or religious services in the rapidly growing city, which prompted missionaries like William Taylor to meet the need, where he held services in the street, using a barrel head as his pulpit.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Crowds would gather to listen to his sermons, and before long he received enough generous donations from successful gold miners and built San Francisco's first church.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] In what has been referred to as the "first world-class gold rush," there was no easy way to travel to California; forty-niners faced hardship and often death on the way.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] At first, most Argonauts, as they were also known, traveled by sea.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] From the East Coast, a sailing voyage around the tip of South America would take four to five months, and cover approximately 18,000 nautical miles (21,000 mi; 33,000 km).
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] An alternative was to sail to the Atlantic side of the Isthmus of Panama, take canoes and mules for a week through the jungle, and then on the Pacific side, wait for a ship sailing for San Francisco.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] There was also a route across Mexico starting at Veracruz.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] The companies providing such transportation generated vast amounts of wealth among their owners, including the U.S.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Mail Steamship Company, the federally subsidized Pacific Mail Steamship Company, and the Accessory Transit Company.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Many gold-seekers took the overland route across the continental United States, particularly along the California Trail.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Each of these routes had its own deadly hazards, from shipwreck to typhoid fever and cholera.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] In the early years of the rush, much of the population growth in the San Francisco area was due to steamship travel from New York City through overland portages in Nicaragua and Panama and then back up by steamship to San Francisco.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] While traveling, many steamships from the eastern seaboard required the passengers to bring kits, which were typically full of personal belongings such as clothes, guidebooks, tools, etc.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] In addition to personal belongings, Argonauts were required to bring barrels full of beef, biscuits, butter, pork, rice, and salt.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] While on the steamships, travelers could talk to each other, smoke, fish, and engage in other activities depending on the ship they traveled.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Still, the dominant activity held throughout the steamships was gambling, which was ironic, since segregation between wealth gaps was prominent throughout the ships.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Everything was segregated between the rich and the poor.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] There were different levels of travel one could pay for to get to California.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] The cheaper steamships tended to have longer routes.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] In contrast, the more expensive ones would get passengers to California quicker.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] There were clear social and economic distinctions between those who traveled together, being that those who spent more money would receive accommodations that others were not allowed.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] They would do this with the clear intent to distinguish their higher class power over those that could not afford those accommodations.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Supply ships arrived in San Francisco with goods to supply the needs of the growing population.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] When hundreds of ships were abandoned after their crews deserted to go into the goldfields, many ships were converted to warehouses, stores, taverns, hotels, and one into a jail.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] As the city expanded and new places were needed on which to build, many ships were destroyed and used as landfills.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Within a few years, there was an important but lesser-known surge of prospectors into far Northern California, specifically into present-day Siskiyou, Shasta and Trinity Counties.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Discovery of gold nuggets at the site of present-day Yreka in 1851 brought thousands of gold-seekers up the Siskiyou Trail and throughout California's northern counties.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Settlements of the gold rush era, such as Portuguese Flat on the Sacramento River, sprang into existence and then faded.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] The gold rush town of Weaverville on the Trinity River today retains the oldest continuously used Taoist temple in California, a legacy of Chinese miners who came.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] While there are not many Gold Rush era ghost towns still in existence, the remains of the once-bustling town of Shasta have been preserved in a California State Historic Park in Northern California.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] By 1850, most of the easily accessible gold had been collected, and attention turned to extracting gold from more difficult locations.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Faced with gold increasingly difficult to retrieve, Americans began to drive out foreigners to get at the most accessible gold that remained.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] The new California State Legislature passed a foreign miners tax of twenty dollars per month ($770 per month as of 2025), and American prospectors began organized attacks on foreign miners, particularly Latin Americans and Chinese.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] In addition, the huge numbers of newcomers were driving Native Americans out of their traditional hunting, fishing, and food-gathering areas.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] To protect their homes and livelihood, some Native Americans responded by attacking the miners.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] This provoked counter-attacks on native villages.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] The Native Americans, out-gunned, were often slaughtered.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Those who escaped massacres were many times unable to survive without access to their food-gathering areas, and they starved to death.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Novelist and poet Joaquin Miller vividly captured one such attack in his semi-autobiographical work, *Life Amongst the Modocs*.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] These first miners were sometimes entire families, of all ethnicities, in which everyone helped in the effort.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Women and children were sometimes found panning next to the men.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Some enterprising families set up boarding houses to accommodate the influx of men; in such cases, the women could bring in steady income while their husbands searched for gold.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Word of the gold rush spread slowly at first.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] The earliest gold-seekers were people who lived near California or people who heard the news from ships on the fastest sailing routes from California.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] The first large group of Americans to arrive were several thousand Oregonians who came down the Siskiyou Trail.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Next came people from the Sandwich Islands, and several thousand Latin Americans, including people from Mexico, from Peru and from as far away as Chile, both by ship and overland.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] By the end of 1848, some 6,000 Argonauts had come to California.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Only a small number (probably fewer than 500) traveled overland from the United States that year.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Some of these "forty-eighters", as the earliest gold-seekers were sometimes called, were able to collect large amounts of easily accessible gold—in some cases, thousands of dollars' worth each day.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Even ordinary prospectors averaged daily gold finds worth 10 to 15 times the daily wage of a laborer on the East Coast.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] A person could work for six months in the goldfields and find the equivalent of six years' wages back home.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Some hoped to get rich quick and return home, and others wished to settle in California.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] By the beginning of 1849, word of the gold rush had spread around the world, and an overwhelming number of gold-seekers and merchants began to arrive from virtually every continent.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] The largest group of forty-niners in 1849 were Americans from the East Coast, arriving by the tens of thousands overland across the continent and along various sailing routes (the term "forty-niner" was derived from the year 1849).
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Many from the East Coast negotiated a crossing of the Appalachian Mountains, taking to riverboats in Pennsylvania, poling the keelboats to Missouri River wagon train assembly ports, and then traveling in a wagon train along the California Trail.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Many others came by way of the Isthmus of Panama and the steamships of the Pacific Mail Steamship Company.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Australians and New Zealanders picked up the news from ships carrying Hawaiian newspapers, and thousands, infected with "gold fever", boarded ships for California.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Forty-niners came from Latin America, particularly from the Mexican mining districts near Sonora and Chile.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Gold-seekers and merchants from Asia, primarily from China, began arriving in 1849, at first in modest numbers to *Gum San* ("Gold Mountain"), the name given to California in Chinese.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] The first immigrants from Europe, reeling from the effects of the Revolutions of 1848 and with a longer distance to travel, began arriving in late 1849, mostly from France, with some Germans, Italians, and Britons.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] It is estimated that approximately 90,000 people arrived in California in 1849—about half by land and half by sea.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Of these, perhaps 50,000 to 60,000 were Americans, and the rest were from other countries.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] By 1855, it is estimated at least 300,000 gold-seekers, merchants, and other immigrants had arrived in California from around the world.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] The largest group continued to be Americans, but there were tens of thousands each of Mexicans, Chinese, Britons, Australians, French, and Latin Americans, together with many smaller groups of miners, such as African Americans, Filipinos, Basques and people from the Ottoman Empire.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] People from small villages in the hills near Genoa, Italy, were among the first to settle permanently in the Sierra Nevada foothills; they brought with them traditional agricultural skills, developed to survive cold winters.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] A modest number of miners were of African ancestry (probably fewer than 4,000) had come from the Southern States, the Caribbean and Brazil.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Several hundred Chinese arrived in California in 1849 and 1850, and in 1852 more than 20,000 landed in San Francisco.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Their distinctive dress and appearance was highly recognizable in the goldfields.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Chinese miners suffered enormously, enduring violent racism from white miners who aimed their frustrations at foreigners.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Further animosity toward the Chinese led to legislation such as the Chinese Exclusion Act and Foreign Miners Tax.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Of the 40,000 people who arrived by ship to the San Francisco Bay in 1849, only 700 were women (including those who were poor, wealthy, entrepreneurs, prostitutes, single, and married).
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] They were of various ethnicities including Anglo-American, African-American, Hispanic, Native, European, Chinese, and Jewish.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] The reasons they came varied: some came with their husbands, refusing to be left behind to fend for themselves, some came because their husbands sent for them, and others came (singles and widows) for the adventure and economic opportunities.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] On the trail many people died from accidents, cholera, fever, and myriad other causes, and many women became widows before even setting eyes on California.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] While in California, women became widows quite frequently due to mining accidents, disease, or mining disputes of their husbands.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Life in the goldfields offered opportunities for women to break from their traditional work.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Because of many thousands of people flooding into California at Sacramento and San Francisco and surrounding areas, the Methodist church deemed it necessary to send missionaries there to preach the gospel, as churches in that part of the state were not to be found.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] The first missionary to arrive was William Taylor who arrived in San Francisco in September 1849.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] For many months he preached in the streets to hundreds of people without salary, and ultimately after saving often generous donations from successful miners, he built and established the first Methodist church in California, and California's first professional hospital.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] When the Gold Rush began, the California goldfields were peculiarly lawless places.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] When gold was discovered at Sutter's Mill, California was still technically part of Mexico, under American military occupation as the result of the Mexican–American War.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] With the signing of the treaty ending the war on February 2, 1848, California became a possession of the United States, but it was not a formal "territory" and did not become a state until September 9, 1850.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] California existed in the unusual condition of a region under military control.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] There was no civil legislature, executive or judicial body for the entire region.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Local residents operated under a confusing and changing mixture of Mexican rules, American principles, and personal dictates.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Lax enforcement of federal laws, such as the Fugitive Slave Act of 1850, encouraged the arrival of free blacks and escaped slaves.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] While the treaty ending the Mexican–American War obliged the United States to honor Mexican land grants, almost all the goldfields were outside those grants.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Instead, the goldfields were primarily on "public land", meaning land formally owned by the United States government.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] However, there were no legal rules yet in place, and no practical enforcement mechanisms.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] The benefit to the forty-niners was that the gold was simply "free for the taking" at first.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] In the goldfields at the beginning, there was no private property, no licensing fees, and no taxes.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] The miners informally adapted Mexican mining law that had existed in California.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] For example, the rules attempted to balance the rights of early arrivers at a site with later arrivers; a "claim" could be "staked" by a prospector, but that claim was valid only as long as it was being actively worked.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Miners worked at a claim only long enough to determine its potential.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] If a claim was deemed as low-value—as most were—miners would abandon the site in search of a better one.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] In the case where a claim was abandoned or not worked upon, other miners would "claim-jump" the land.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] "Claim-jumping" meant that a miner began work on a previously claimed site.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Disputes were often handled personally and violently, and were sometimes addressed by groups of prospectors acting as arbitrators.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] This often led to heightened ethnic tensions.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] In some areas the influx of many prospectors could lead to a reduction of the existing claim size by simple pressure.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Approximately four hundred million years ago, California lay at the bottom of a large sea; underwater volcanoes deposited lava and minerals (including gold) onto the sea floor.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] By tectonic forces these minerals and rocks came to the surface of the Sierra Nevada, and eroded.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Water carried the exposed gold downstream and deposited it in quiet gravel beds along the sides of old rivers and streams.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] The forty-niners first focused their efforts on these deposits of gold.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Because the gold in the California gravel beds was so richly concentrated, early forty-niners were able to retrieve loose gold flakes and nuggets with their hands, or simply "pan" for gold in rivers and streams.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Panning cannot take place on a large scale, and industrious miners and groups of miners graduated to placer mining, using "cradles" and "rockers" or "long-toms" to process larger volumes of gravel.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Miners would also engage in "coyoteing", a method that involved digging a shaft 6 to 13 meters (20 to 43 ft) deep into placer deposits along a stream.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Tunnels were then dug in all directions to reach the richest veins of pay dirt.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] In the most complex placer mining, groups of prospectors would divert the water from an entire river into a sluice alongside the river and then dig for gold in the newly exposed river bottom.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Mixed groups of Chileans and Mexicans were the first to apply this technique which required collaborative work which was something that was more common among Chileans when compared to Anglo Americans.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Modern estimates are that as much as 12 million ounces (370 t) of gold were removed in the first five years of the Gold Rush.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Chilean miners, coming from an area with a long mining tradition, were influential in California.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Many Euroamerican miners learned from them and from Sonorans.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Chileans are credited to have introduced the *batea* gold pan (dish made of wood) and the *trapiche* to California.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] The *trapiche* became known as the Chilean mill and compared favourable to similar technology introduced by Mexicans.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] In the next stage, by 1853, hydraulic mining was used on ancient gold-bearing gravel beds on hillsides and bluffs in the goldfields.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] In a modern style of hydraulic mining first developed in California, and later used around the world, a high-pressure hose directed a powerful stream or jet of water at gold-bearing gravel beds.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] The loosened gravel and gold would then pass over sluices, with the gold settling to the bottom where it was collected.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] By the mid-1880s, it is estimated that 11 million troy ounces (340 t) of gold (worth approximately US$15 billion at December 2010 prices) had been recovered by hydraulic mining.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] A byproduct of these extraction methods was that large amounts of gravel, silt, heavy metals, and other pollutants went into streams and rivers.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Court rulings (1882 Gold Run and 1884 "Sawyer Act") and 1893 federal legislation limited hydraulic mining in California.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] As of 1999 many areas still bear the scars of hydraulic mining, since the resulting exposed earth and downstream gravel deposits do not support plant life.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] After the gold rush had concluded, gold recovery operations continued.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] The final stage to recover loose gold was to prospect for gold that had slowly washed down into the flat river bottoms and sandbars of California's Central Valley and other gold-bearing areas of California (such as Scott Valley in Siskiyou County).
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] By the late 1890s, dredging technology (also invented in California) had become economical, and it is estimated that more than 20 million troy ounces (620 t) were recovered by dredging.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Both during the gold rush and in the decades that followed, gold-seekers also engaged in hard-rock mining, extracting the gold directly from the rock that contained it (typically quartz), usually by digging and blasting to follow and remove veins of the gold-bearing quartz.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Chilean miners in particular had experience in this type of mining.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Once the gold-bearing rocks were brought to the surface, the rocks were crushed and the gold separated, either using separation in water, using its density difference from quartz sand, or by washing the sand over copper plates coated with mercury (with which gold forms an amalgam).
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Loss of mercury in the amalgamation process was a source of environmental contamination.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Eventually, hard-rock mining became the single largest source of gold produced in the Gold Country.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] The total production of gold in California from then until now is estimated at 118 million troy ounces (3,700 t).
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Recent scholarship confirms that merchants made far more money than miners during the gold rush.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] The wealthiest man in California during the early years of the rush was Samuel Brannan, a tireless self-promoter, shopkeeper and newspaper publisher.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Brannan opened the first supply stores in Sacramento, Coloma, and other spots in the goldfields.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Just as the rush began, he purchased all the prospecting supplies available in San Francisco and resold them at a substantial profit.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Some gold-seekers made a significant amount of money.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] On average, half the gold-seekers made a modest profit, after taking all expenses into account; economic historians have suggested that white miners were more successful than black, Indian, or Chinese miners.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] However, taxes such as the California foreign miners tax passed in 1851, targeted mainly Latino miners and kept them from making as much money as whites, who did not have any taxes imposed on them.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] In California most late arrivals made little or wound up losing money.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Similarly, many unlucky merchants set up in settlements that disappeared, or which succumbed to one of the calamitous fires that swept the towns that sprang up.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] By contrast, a businessman who went on to great success was Levi Strauss, who first began selling denim overalls in San Francisco in 1853.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Other businessmen reaped great rewards in retail, shipping, entertainment, lodging, or transportation.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Boardinghouses, food preparation, sewing, and laundry were highly profitable businesses often run by women (married, single, or widowed) who realized men would pay well for a service done by a woman.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Brothels also brought in large profits, especially when combined with saloons and gaming houses.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] By 1855, the economic climate had changed dramatically.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Gold could be retrieved profitably from the goldfields only by medium to large groups of workers, either in partnerships or as employees.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] By the mid-1850s, it was the owners of these gold-mining companies who made the money.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Also, the population and economy of California had become large and diverse enough that money could be made in a wide variety of conventional businesses.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Once extracted, the gold itself took many paths.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] First, much of the gold was used locally to purchase food, supplies and lodging for the miners.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] It also went towards entertainment, which consisted of anything from a traveling theater to alcohol, gambling, and prostitutes.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] These transactions often took place using the recently recovered gold, carefully weighed out.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] These merchants and vendors, in turn, used the gold to purchase supplies from ship captains or packers bringing goods to California.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] The gold then left California aboard ships or mules to go to the makers of the goods from around the world.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] A second path was the Argonauts themselves who, having personally acquired a sufficient amount, sent the gold home, or returned home taking with them their hard-earned "diggings".
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] For example, one estimate is that some US$80 million worth of California gold (equivalent to US$2.8 billion today) was sent to France by French prospectors and merchants.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] A majority of the gold went back to New York City brokerage houses.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] As the gold rush progressed, local banks and gold dealers issued "banknotes" or "drafts"—locally accepted paper currency—in exchange for gold, and private mints created private gold coins.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] With the building of the San Francisco Mint in 1854, gold bullion was turned into official United States gold coins for circulation.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] The gold was also later sent by California banks to U.S. national banks in exchange for national paper currency to be used in the booming California economy.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] The arrival of hundreds of thousands of new people in California within a few years, compared to a population of some 15,000 Europeans and *Californios* beforehand, had many dramatic effects.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] The gold rush propelled California from a sleepy, little-known backwater to a center of the global imagination and the destination of hundreds of thousands of people.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] The new immigrants often showed remarkable inventiveness and civic mindedness.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] For example, in the midst of the gold rush, towns and cities were chartered, a state constitutional convention was convened, a state constitution written, elections held, and representatives sent to Washington, D.C., to negotiate the admission of California as a state.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Large-scale agriculture (California's second "Gold Rush") began during this time.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Roads, schools, churches, and civic organizations quickly came into existence.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] The vast majority of the immigrants were Americans.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Pressure grew for better communications and political connections to the rest of the United States, leading to statehood for California on September 9, 1850, in the Compromise of 1850 as the 31st state of the United States.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Between 1847 and 1870, the population of San Francisco increased from 500 to 150,000.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] The Gold Rush wealth and population increase led to significantly improved transportation between California and the East Coast.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] The Panama Railway, spanning the Isthmus of Panama, was finished in 1855.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Steamships, including those owned by the Pacific Mail Steamship Company, began regular service from San Francisco to Panama, where passengers, goods and mail would take the train across the Isthmus and board steamships headed to the East Coast.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] *Central America*, ended in disaster as the ship sank in a hurricane off the coast of the Carolinas in 1857, with approximately three tons of California gold aboard.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Urban indians had lived in California since Spanish times.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] The millrace where gold was first discovered had been dug by a crew of Indians hired by John Sutter.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] The human and environmental costs of the Gold Rush were substantial.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Native Americans, dependent on traditional hunting, gathering and agriculture, became the victims of starvation and disease, as gravel, silt and toxic chemicals from prospecting operations killed fish and destroyed habitats.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] The surge in the mining population also resulted in the disappearance of game and food gathering locales as gold camps and other settlements were built amidst them.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Later farming spread to supply the settlers' camps, taking more land away from the Native Americans.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] In some areas, systematic attacks against tribespeople in or near mining districts occurred.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Various conflicts were fought between natives and settlers.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Miners often saw Native Americans as impediments to their mining activities.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Ed Allen, interpretive lead for Marshall Gold Discovery State Historic Park, reported that there were times when miners would kill up to 50 or more Natives in one day.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Retribution attacks on solitary miners could result in larger scale attacks against Native populations, at times tribes or villages not involved in the original act.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] During the 1852 Bridge Gulch Massacre, a group of settlers attacked a band of Wintu Indians in response to the killing of a citizen named J.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] After his killing, the sheriff led a group of men to track down the Indians, whom the men then attacked, killing more than 150 Wintu people.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Only three children survived the massacre that was against a different band of Wintu than the one that had killed Anderson.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Furthermore, California stood in opposition to ratifying the eighteen treaties signed between tribal leaders and federal agents in 1851.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] The state government, in support of miner activities, funded and supported private militia groups, appropriating over $1 million towards the funding and operation of the paramilitary organizations.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Peter Burnett, California's first governor, declared that California was a battleground between the races and that there were only two options towards California Indians: extermination or removal.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] "That a war of extermination will continue to be waged between the two races until the Indian race becomes extinct, must be expected.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] After the initial boom had ended, explicitly anti-foreign and racist attacks, laws, and confiscatory taxes sought to drive out foreigners—in addition to Native Americans—from the mines, especially the Chinese and Latin American immigrants mostly from Sonora, Mexico, and Chile.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Spanish-speaking immigrants tended to group together and among these Chileans tended to assume leadership which made outsiders call all of them "Chilean".
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] This leadership was particularly visible when Spanish-speaking miners had to confront "Anglo" miners.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Chilean miners are known to have resisted eviction by various means, both legal and by the use of revenge attacks culminating in the Chile War of 1849.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] The toll on the American immigrants was severe as well: one in twelve forty-niners perished, as the death and crime rates during the Gold Rush were extraordinarily high, and the resulting vigilantism also took its toll.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] The gold rush stimulated economies around the world as well.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Farmers in Chile, Australia, and Hawaii found a huge new market for their food; British manufactured goods were in high demand; clothing and even prefabricated houses arrived from China.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] The return of large amounts of California gold to pay for these goods raised prices and stimulated investment and the creation of jobs around the world.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Australian prospector Edward Hargraves, noting similarities between the geography of California and his home country, returned to Australia to discover gold and spark the Australian gold rushes.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Preceding the gold rush, the United States was on a bi-metallic standard, but the sudden increase in physical gold supply increased the relative value of physical silver and drove silver money from circulation.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] The increase in gold supply also created a monetary supply shock.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Within a few years after the end of the gold rush, in 1863, the groundbreaking ceremony for the western leg of the first transcontinental railroad was held in Sacramento.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] The line's completion, some six years later, financed in part with Gold Rush money, united California with the central and eastern United States.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Travel that had taken weeks or even months could now be accomplished in days.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] As the California gold rush brought a disproportionate population of men and set an environment of experimental lawlessness separate from the bounds of standard society, conventional American gender roles came into question.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] In the large absence of women, these migrant young men were made to reorganize their social and sexual practices, leading to cross-gender practices that most often took place as cross-dressing.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Dance events were a notable social space for cross-dressing, where a piece of cloth (such as a handkerchief or sackcloth patch) would denote a 'woman.' Beyond social events, these subverted gender expectations continued into domestic duties as well.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Though cross-dressing occurred most frequently with men as women, the reverse also applied.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] These miners and merchants of various genders and gendered appearances, encouraged by the social fluidity and population limitations of the Wild West, shaped the beginnings of San Francisco's prominent queer history.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] California's name became indelibly connected with the gold rush, and fast success in a new world became known as the "California Dream".
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] California was perceived as a place of new beginnings, where great wealth could reward hard work and good luck.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] (2) California state route shield, with the number 49 and shaped like a miner's spade.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Overnight California gained the international reputation as the "golden state".
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Generations of immigrants have been attracted by the California Dream.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] California farmers, oil drillers, movie makers, airplane builders, computer and microchip makers, and "dot-com" entrepreneurs have each had their boom times in the decades after the gold rush.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] In addition, the standard route shield of state highways in California is in the shape of a miner's spade to honor the California gold rush.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] Today, the aptly named State Route 49 travels through the Sierra Nevada foothills, connecting many Gold Rush-era towns such as Placerville, Auburn, Grass Valley, Nevada City, Coloma, Jackson, and Sonora.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] This state highway also passes very near Columbia State Historic Park, a protected area encompassing the historic business district of the town of Columbia; the park has preserved many gold rush–era buildings, which are presently occupied by tourist-oriented businesses.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] The literary history of the gold rush is reflected in the works of Mark Twain (*The Celebrated Jumping Frog of Calaveras County*), Bret Harte (*A Millionaire of Rough-and-Ready*), Joaquin Miller (*Life Amongst the Modocs*), and many others.
[src:california-gold-rush/california-gold-rush] The San Francisco 49ers, a professional American football team based in the San Francisco Bay Area and competing in the National Football League, are named after miners.
